animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Fill out an Adoption Application
Mia is a 6 year old female Dogo Argentino mix. She also comes from a rural shelter in North Carolina where she was not doing well. After being transferred to rescue in Norfolk , Va she spent 4 years there where her name was changed to Elsa because she was completely frozen with fear.We have given her much to be happy about and along with that her new name, Mia.She would not walk on a leash or play with other dogs and rarely let you pet her without cowering. She has transformed into a well adjusted, happy girl! Mia loves to walk on a leash and although she sometimes puts the brakes on...a stable pack leader with just a bit of pressure can move her right through. She also loves to be outside and loves the company of other dogs. You will find her curled up in a bed of leaves relaxing in the sun on a warm afternoon.Mia is still shy and will still cower if approached too quickly, she is also hard of hearing which may contribute to her insecureness but overall she has made huge progress and now deserves a home to call all hers.Again, Mia will need a leader to continue to overcome her quirks but she is an amazing girl.She is crate trained and potty trained. She rides great in the car. She will struggle with nails so that will take some patience and an extra hand. Mia is also up to date on shots, microchipped and spayed.Located in Knoxville, MD
Our rescue policy requires the following:

Adopters must have their primary residence in one of the following states: Pennsylvania, Ohio, New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland, West Virginia, Virginia, and parts of North Carolina and and parts of New York.
We will not adopt a giant breed dog to homes where the dog will have access to highly varnished hardwood steps inside the home. Any inside steps to which the dog(s) have access, must have carpeting, securely fixed stair treads, or a non-skid surface. We encourage you to remediate potential safety issues while your application is under review, prior to the home visit.
Methods or devices using pain or force on the dog to control the dog, or to deter undesirable behavior is prohibited.
Applications for giant breed dogs must be submitted by the property owner.
Homes with children under 6 years of age will not be approved for adoption.
Homes with children should have a fenced yard.
Pets currently in the applicant's home must have a history of appropriate veterinary care. Veterinary records will be checked.
All references must be checked before any visitation of the dog is permitted at the foster home.
All family members must be present during the home visit to the applicant's home.
Any dog(s) in the applicant's home must have an introductory meeting with the rescue dog being considered, before any adoption can be completed.
Homes with intact dogs will not be approved for adoption. Exceptions to this policy can be found on the Adoptable Dog Page.

For additional information please review our FAQs or contact: mastiffstomutts@gmail.com

Akita is such a fun girl! She's happy to greet you with a big smile on her face. Even though she's technically a senior, she's still quite active and enjoys long walks or hikes. Do you have room in your heart for a sweet, senior girl like Akita?

animal.description:
Derek (and his sister, Meredith) were brought to us as strays no one ever came for. He is the shyest of the two but very sweet natured. Not leash trained. One-two years old and about 45 lbs.

ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00 . This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

Foster Homes Needed!

Do you have time and room in your life for a foster dog?

http://www.muttloverescue.org/foster.html

*****************

Tracy is a beautiful chestnut brown bully girl, about 1 year old and weighs 49 lbs. Tracy is energetic, outgoing and playful, and is fine with children and other dogs. She was picked up as a stray, but we know she was in a home, so she's probably house trained. She is very good on a leash, and would be a great walking companion. She is very loving and sweet, and really appreciates affection. Her right ear was split somehow but it is now repaired, and she's spayed and fully vetted. She is totally healthy and ready for her new home. Please email Dee at k9rescueva@gmail.com to schedule a meeting with this sweet girl.

**BECAUSE OF OUR REQUIREMENT FOR A HOME VISIT, WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO ADOPT TO HOMES IN THE NORTHERN VA / MARYLAND / DC METRO AREA**

We have adoption events EVERY SATURDAY from 12-3 p.m. Please note that not all dogs can attend every event, so if you are interested in meeting a particular dog, please complete a no-obligation application on our website at http://www.muttloverescue.org/application.html OR write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

Upcoming adoption events:

Mutt Love Rescue is doing everything we can to ensure the health and safety of our volunteers and adopters while continuing our mission to find homes for as many dogs as possible.

Effective immediately, we will not be holding our weekly adoption events. Dogs available for adoption can be met by appointment only. Potential adopters should submit an online application at http://muttloverescue.org/application.html. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to let you know the next steps.

We are always desperate for foster homes, now more than ever. If you are interested in fostering during this difficult time, please complete an application... unless you are a previous adopter/foster, then you can just contact us via phone (703-988-2608) or email (adopt@muttloverescue.org) to tell us which dog you want to foster!

For information on sponsoring this dog, please write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

WE NEED FOSTER HOMES! FOR MORE INFORMATION, PLEASE EMAIL ADOPT@MUTTLOVERESCUE.ORG.

Visit us on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/muttloverescue
Follow us on Twitter: @Muttlove_Rescue

ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.

Betsy is a 2 1/2 year old collie/lab mix. Unfortunately the family that adopted her no longer had time for her and she had become a bit overweight and a couch potato. We were also told that she did not like other animals and had a strong prey drive. Since coming to us, she has learned to walk on a leash always with another dog, she enjoys the company and play with our pack and has lost several pounds through activity and exercise.She is full of energy and is quite food motivated and therefore eager to learn.Betsy does do better with larger male dogs or young nonchallenging females. She is not recommended to be around cats.She does great riding in the car, and dosent mind a nail trim. She is behaved at the vet, is crate trained and potty trained.Betsy is up to date on shots, spayed and microchipped. She was treated for heartworm and is now free and clear and is maintained on a monthly preventative.Located in Knoxville, MD
Our rescue policy requires the following:

Adopters must have their primary residence in one of the following states: Pennsylvania, Ohio, New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland, West Virginia, Virginia, and parts of North Carolina and and parts of New York.
We will not adopt a giant breed dog to homes where the dog will have access to highly varnished hardwood steps inside the home. Any inside steps to which the dog(s) have access, must have carpeting, securely fixed stair treads, or a non-skid surface. We encourage you to remediate potential safety issues while your application is under review, prior to the home visit.
Methods or devices using pain or force on the dog to control the dog, or to deter undesirable behavior is prohibited.
Applications for giant breed dogs must be submitted by the property owner.
Homes with children under 6 years of age will not be approved for adoption.
Homes with children should have a fenced yard.
Pets currently in the applicant's home must have a history of appropriate veterinary care. Veterinary records will be checked.
All references must be checked before any visitation of the dog is permitted at the foster home.
All family members must be present during the home visit to the applicant's home.
Any dog(s) in the applicant's home must have an introductory meeting with the rescue dog being considered, before any adoption can be completed.
Homes with intact dogs will not be approved for adoption. Exceptions to this policy can be found on the Adoptable Dog Page.

For additional information please review our FAQs or contact: mastiffstomutts@gmail.com

animal.description:
PLEASE READ ENTIRE DESCRIPTION BEFORE INQUIRING

Include your location when you email us for an application. Emails that don't include your location may not receive a response. 

If you send more than one email you will not receive a response. It clogs our inbox up and slows down our response time.

Only email if you are interested in adopting both girls, we will not be separating them. 

Tiny 5lb,  6 month old littermates, Opal & Pearl are adorable and playful. They love their canine foster sisters and are fine with the cats.  They are pretty good sleepers if you keep them awake till 10:00pm they usually sleep till 6:15-6:30am when Pearl let’s you know it’s time to get up! Pearl is definitely more vocal (nice way of saying yappy) and Opal is much more quiet. They do take a good long nap during the day and a short nap around 7:00pm. They love belly rubs but they aren’t pocket/purse or lap dogs. They like their fuzzy cozy bed and their stuffed toys.  Opal will find any little thing on the floor (or steal off the coffee table) and run and hide with her treasure while Pearl is the stinker that will chew electrical cords (or earbuds ?) if she gets the chance! They are both very active and get around really well in spite of their leg issues.  Per the orthopedic assessment, Pearl will need surgery to repair her leg (luxating patella) but not sure Opal would benefit enough from the surgery to warrant putting her through such drastic procedure.  These girls are very bonded and love each other very much. We are looking for a wonderful, amazing, loving home together since they are very bonded. We also are looking for a home that can be able to afford the surgery that Pearl will need in about 6 more months. They are spayed, fully vaccinated, tested negative for heartworm and Tick Born diseases, dewormed, microchipped, on Bravecto and Heart worm preventative.  Opal and Pearl are available for adoption now. Although good with kids, we are looking to place these girls in an adult only home due to their size. 

A home check is required. Yolo County adopters preferred, but will consider other locations. If you are more than 100 miles away from Yolo County please be aware that there may be a small additional expense associated with travel cost. 

If you are interested in adoption Opal and Pearl, email us and we will send you an adoption application. (include your location in the email) The adoption fee for each puppy $650. 

*Vetting includes: Neuter/spay, microchip, age appropriate vaccinations, deworming, heartworm test, flea preventative, heart worm preventative (including the remainder of their 6-month supply), and any other necessary vet care.

animal.description:
I'm chilling in a foster home currently. To inquire about me or to arrange a meeting, please email fosterdogadopt@orphansofthestorm.org

My name is Nina and I am five years old. I have lived with a foster family and they have found that I enjoy spending time outside. I have been kayaking, camping, and doing a ton of hiking in various places. I even like spending time outside with my foster parents while they tend to their yard. Here are a couple of notes you may want to know about me:
Separation anxiety - Yes, I do have it. I do not like to be alone. Overcoming separation anxiety is a work in progress. My current foster parents work from home so I enjoy the company of my foster parents most of the day, which means I get to walk them often. However, they have left me home alone between 3-6 hours on four separate occasions and I have not damaged anything! Nothing! Nada! Before my foster parents leave me home alone they walk me, feed me, and I have access to toys to keep me entertained. And when they return, I walk them again as a reward for my good behavior.
Crate trained - No, I am not crate trained and I do not appear to like them. My foster parents report that I fear enclosed spaces - this includes bathrooms, mudrooms, and crates - so the crate is really not my thing. Did I mention that I have not destroyed anything in their home? I have not even played with the multiple plants they have on the floor inside their home nor with their window dressings. 
Dog reactive - Yes, I do react to some dogs when I am out on walks. I also like to chase squirrels and other critters. At the shelter, I have had no problems playing with other dogs. My foster parents also reported that I do well while on walks at campgrounds where dogs abound. For the most part, I walk well on a leash. My foster parents have found that I like to run on a leash - which may distract me from chasing squirrels and reacting to other dogs.
Dashing out the door - I have yet to work on this, but my foster parents are pretty diligent in checking where I am before opening the door. Yes, I did leave the house one time, but that was because my foster mom left the backdoor ajar and I snuck out. Wouldn't you? I took them on an unsolicited brisk walk, but they caught up to me soon after and returned me home.
Health - I am healthy. I am taking some meds for joints and I am on prescription diet for allergies. 
Beggar - No, I do not beg for food. I leave you alone when you eat and respect your space. Isn't' that nice of me? 
Barky - No, I do not have this trait either. I don't bark just for the sake of barking. You know how some dogs bark, and bark, and bark, and bark? Not me. No, I don't do that. 
Clingy - No, I do not have this trait. I do like being in the same room as my foster parents, but I do not cling to them. Nor do I jump on people when I meet them for the first time or when my foster parents return home.
Rubs and getting groomed - I absolutely love people doing these two things to me! I will roll on my back or melt in your arms if you brush my luxurious white coat. 
House broken - Of course I am house broken! I have not had any accidents during my stay with my foster parents. I have the outmost respect for their stuff.
Come check me out! I will not disappoint.

animal.description:
Yo!

Mark here at your service!  

Here's my story:
 An older couple began to see a very pregnant gem (my mommy) near their county home.  They saw her for a number of days then she disappeared.  Weeks later they saw her again coming out from underneath an abandoned house.  It wasn't long before they began to see 10 puppies joining her.  I was one of those puppies.

My mother would come and go, and then one day she never returned.  :(

The kind couple began collecting us puppies and moving us to their backyard, offering  us food and safety.  They worked diligently to find us families and were successful with 4 of us, until that changed.. The kind gentleman suffered a heart attack and his sweet bride fell off a ladder breaking her collar bone.  The rest of us puppies were still well cared for, but all other activities regarding the puppies had stopped.

What would happen to us now???  Well Lucies Project was contacted, and they are taking us in a few at a time as space becomes available.  There are 3 of us here now, so that leaves 3 more of our siblings still to come.

We don't know why our mom left us, only other than to assume she could see that we would be well taken care of.  We miss her, but am glad she at least got us to safety.

Do you think maybe you might want one of us?  We are truly adorable and would love nothing more than to play or cuddle with you.  We really want a family of our own.  Come see us and we will steal your heart!

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description: Meet Spike! He is an 11-month-old, neutered, male, Shepherd/Labrador Retriever mix. Spike is a very sweet and sociable dog he loves to meet new people! Although he is so sweet, Spike is also very energetic and he jumps on pretty much all sizes of people and with him being such a large dog we do not recommend he go to a home with small children. Spike would benefit greatly being in a home with someone who has plenty of time to exercise him regularly and work with him on basic obedience training. He would make a GREAT running, walking, or workout partner! Spike loves other dogs and would do great with another large dog that he can play with to burn off some of his energy.  We are not sure how Spike does with cats or other pets in the home, because he has never really been around them in the time he has been with us. Spike also needs someone who can help him work on his potty training. He does well if kept on a regular schedule but he will have accidents indoors if not given enough potty breaks. Spike is current on his vaccinations and he is now ready to find his new forever family. If you are interested in a sweet and fun new running partner then Spike is your guy! Come by the shelter and meet Spike today, or call us for more information.

animal.description:
Pupdate.  Hi it's me Amelia, I am making progress.  I am learning that I like to play with my foster siblings, I like to play with toys, I really like walks.  I am getting more comfortable when we meet new people and pups on walks.  Everyone is really nice to me.  Please submit an application if you would like to welcome me into your home and are willing to be patient with me learning new things.

Original
Hi, my name is Amelia. I recently came into VIP Rescue and will be looking for my new home soon!  I’ve got a whole lot to learn about being a dog. I have 3 dogs, at my foster home, helping me with for my behavior and I progress every single day since I got here!!  I am very smart and although I’m kinda cautious, I truly do enjoy learning new things and am getting more comfortable every passing day with all these new experiences.  I am potty trained, I am learning the leash thing.  I need my new home to offer lots of love and patience,  I need a confident dog to be my forever friend and sibling.  I need  home with a fenced yard. I’m not picky about age or size, if they had a playful personality that will help me.  I just need another dog around for comfort and security, I really want to learn from them and I like to try to play. 

I am eagerly looking for my perfect forever person or family to call my very own!  A quiet adult home would be best.  A meet and greet will be required. 

Amelia is thought to be approximately 3 years old and weighs 28 lbs. I am most likely a terrier mix.  I am spayed, current on my shots, microchipped, and on flea and heartworm prevention.  I am heart worm positive. This means I have to take things easy for a while. I also must go see my doctor to get treatments so you have to be available to take me to Palm Harbor. My new family must be in Pinellas, West Pasco or NW Hillsborough.  We are accepting applications from experienced pet parents who already have a confident, friendly dog in the home and a fenced yard. Please submit your application to VIPRescue.org. And please share this post to help Amelia find her forever home. 

if you would like to know more about this dog, please complete an adoption application so that our volunteers  may contact you.    To do so, go to our web site:  http://viprescue.org/jobs/apply/?j=772

All of our available dogs for adoption are are on our website at:  
http://viprescue.org/available-for-adoption/

Check us out on FACEBOOK and learn more about our adoptions and current events:   
 https://www.facebook.com/VIPRESCUEFLORIDA/

THANK YOU for thinking Rescue,
VIP RESCUE OF FLORIDA

animal.description:
My name is Hank. Aren't I just so handsome?? I am a 1-2 year old Great Pyrenees. I was found wandering some dirt roads in rural Arkansas. I had been wandering for awhile and looked everywhere for my owner. Some nice people at Five Rivers Animal Aid, found me and looked for my owner, but none was found. The people that rescued me got rid of all my ticks and worms. My blood work is good now and I am gaining weight. 

I'm a friendly and active guy. I need a family that likes to walk and hike. I am social and would prefer to be with my family and not be left alone. If you can't keep your eye on me, chew toys help to keep me busy. And remember to keep the kitchen counter clean of food or I am liable to eat whatever is left for me there! Other dogs are fun to play with and I'm gentle with children. I am eager to please and most of the time I come when called especially if I know I'm going to get pets. I am house trained, walk well on a leash, and do fine in the car. I will come to you neutered, up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, and up to date on heartworm and flea/tick preventatives. 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved, you must also pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. Children in the home must be at least 10 years of age. I can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, and Arkansas. My rescue is able to transport me to those states. If you would like to give me a furever home, please fill out an application on my rescue's website. 

Being fostered in Holden, MO

animal.description:
Howlo there,

I'm Nelson.  If you know anything about my breed, you know that my smeller is always set on overtime!

I was found running in the highway by a kind disabled woman.  She asked her neighbors about me and found my owner.  Great right??  Wrong...2 days later there I was again in highway dodging vehicles.  We aren't too well known for our common sense.  Our smellers just seem to get the best of us!  Anyway, the same kind lady repeated the process of returning me a couple of times.  On the last return home, my owner said she didn't want me anymore....what??  Why Mom???

The kind disabled lady was now in a pinch.  She just simply could not handle a large, friendly, nosy boy like me.  She also could not afford to care for me, nor did she have room for me to stay either.  I need at least a six foot fence to keep me in.  

I'm not a bad dog at all.  I just need a family who is used to having a hound dog around.  You see, we a really are a handful to keep focused once our noses get the best of us.  And, we like to share our howling, I mean singing love ballads to you.  

I'm definitely a character too.  I mean, you know I like to have fun.  I like to run and play and chase the occasional raccoon.  That is my specialty you know.  I'm very trainable.  I know there are many of my ancestors out there who have won many a coon huntin' trophy or two.

Kids??  You have kids??  I would be the BEST thing for them!  I can keep them out of trouble and  occupied with training me, and in turn they are keeping me occupied as well!  It's a win-win people...come on!

I'm sweet and handsome and kinda cuddly, but not for too long.  A guys gotta keep his image you know if he's gonna be a trophy winner.

So what do you say?  It's time to come see me and take me home.  Covid has kept your family inside too long.  Let's go!!  HOWWWWLLLLLL!!!!

animal.description: This is Ginger, her name matches her perfectly because she is a beautfiul Ginger color. Do not let her intimidate you or discourage you she is just trying to get to know you. Once you spend a couple minutes with her she is the most loving and friendly dog. Once she gets to know you she is very loyal and you will create a strong bond with her. She is on the larger side and for that reason we would not like her to go to a house with small children. She will need a home that can understand her personal space but knows exactly when she wants belly rubs. She has an amazing personailty that will shine through if you take her into our play room. Ginger is around 5 years old and is looking for another chance at a forever home. She has lots of energy and will climb in your lab as she wiggles. Her previous owners say that she is good with other dogs but a meet and greet is always encouraged to insure that she is a good match with your family. She isn't a fan of the vet and has anxiety about it but she will grow to learn that the vet is a good place that will keep her healthy. She is already spayed and up-to-date on all of her vaccines. If you think Ginger would be a great addition to your life please do not hesitate to ask any questions or meet with her outside of her kennel. Meet our sweet 6 year old German Shepherd mixed breed Ginger. Ginger arrived at the shelter in 2015 as a stray from Georgetown Delaware. She was adopted in 2015 but later returned to the shelter due to her owner moving and unable to have pets where he was moving to. She came back in 2018 and has been with us ever since. Here is what we know about her. She loves the people that take care of her. She is comfortable with them. She can adjust quicker with female strangers vs male strangers even though it was a man who adopted her many years ago. Ginger is what is known as a resource guarder. Resource guarding refers to a dog displaying behavior such as growling, snapping, etc. This type of behavior is intended to convince other dogs or humans to stay away from a treasure or resource. The resource can be food, treats, toys, a place (crate), or occasionally even a person. What does all this mean? Simply put Ginger needs to get to know you first. This may take several visits for to even feel comfortable to come up to you and pet her. Even after that happens in a new home she would require the same amount of patience from her new family or potential home visitors. She would do best in a home as a single dog with older people. Small children are just not in the cards for Ginger. She is not deemed animal aggressive she just prefers not to have animals jumping on her. This pet has been spayed/neutered, vaccinated (age appropriate), microchipped, and tested for heartworm (age appropriate). They also receive monthly heartworm prevention and flea/tick while they stay with our shelter. If you are interested in seeing this pet please ask the front desk to call for a kennel tech. Once she gets to know you she is very loyal and you will create a strong bond with her. She has an amazing personailty that will shine through if you take her into our play room. She has lots of energy and will climb in your lab as she wiggles.

animal.description:
pet id 46105252

Carson has moved into a foster home!  He had a sleepover with one of his Train-A-Bull team members and did so well they kept him to foster.  

He's in the rowdy "teenager" phase most dogs go through but is super smart, loves to be with his people, is very cuddly, is housetrained, crate trained and has done awesome only chewing on toys he is meant to chew on.  He walks great and is learning more obedience each day.

He is very dog friendly and is in training to learn how to communicate with his dog pals. His best match would be a well balanced and confident dog that could  be a role model and an owner that understands dog playstyles.  

Cats are unknown, but he does have a strong prey drive so we are guessing it is best to go to a cat free home.  

He's living in his foster home with a 5 year old child and does really well with her but their interactions are closely monitored by the foster mom.  

He was a stray so we don't know for sure his mix or age. He is on the smaller side, about 40 pounds and is about 12-18 months old.  

As a Train-A-Bull sponsored dog he comes with the support of a professional trainer and his foster family to help him adjust to his new home.  If you think he is a good fit for your lifestyle please contact us today at cbas_sponsorship@yahoo.com for more details and to set up a meet and greet!







Because of the COVID19 situation, the shelter is closed to the general public. If you would like to meet any of the adoptable dogs, please fill out an application online (if you are not already pre-approved) , call the shelter, and leave a message with your name and phone number and the dog you're interested in. Have patience, and they will call you back when they can. From there, a time will be scheduled for you to come and meet the dog. Please be patient, and remember they are very short staffed at the moment.

Applications can be found at https://friendsofcbas.org/adopt

animal.description:
DCELL NEEDS A FOSTER OR LOVING FOREVER HOME!!!
Fosters make it possible for Dogs XL to save and care for homeless and abandoned dogs! To learn about fostering dogs like DCell, please contact us at http://www.dogsxlrescue.org/volunteer/foster

Name: D-Cell (pka Diesel)

Breed: Great Dane

Approximate Age: 2 years

Approximate Weight: 108 pounds

Currently Living at: Local foster home

 

Meet D-Cell! D-Cell is a gorgeous lanky Great Dane who picked up by animal control after he was found wandering the streets as a stray. Animal control was able to locate his owners, but sadly, they did not want him back because he has previously escaped a number of times. This handsome Houdini would do best with a family who has a tall, secure fence. DCell has no leash manners so needs an adopter committed to working with him on that and who doesn’t rely on leash walks for the time being. D-Cell is a friendly, happy guy who does well with other dogs and is super affectionate! D-Cell likes to rest his head on his human's shoulder and lean up against them for pets and love! D-Cell loves kids, but he doesn't understand that he shouldn't play rough with them, so he's not a good match for a family with young children.
 
D-Cell is still working on house and crate training, and he seems to have had next to no training, so he needs a family who will enroll him in obedience training ASAP and get to work on his manners. He puts anything and everything in his mouth and he likes to rearrange his foster's house and sometimes enjoys gnawing on furniture when he's bored, so he'll need to be crated when his family is out of the house. D-Cell is very food motivated, but he's not the brightest bulb, so he needs some time to pick up new cues. At just 2 years old, he's still got a lot of puppy in him and he's certainly not aware of his size! D-Cell could afford to put on a couple pounds and he may still have some growing to do, but he's on the small side for a Dane. Don't doubt his strength, though, because this boy is STRONG! D-Cell will make a wonderful companion for a loving forever family willing to put in the work to teach him to be a good canine citizen. Apply today to meet D-Cell! 
 

D-Cell needs a foster or a loving forever home to lavish love and attention on him. Please open your heart and home to D-Cell!


The adoption fee for this dog is $300, which includes the cost of heartworm treatment and routine vetting, including vaccinations and spay/neuter.

 

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out the application online at http://www.dogsxlrescue.org/adopt/adoption-questionnaire

 

Thank you for considering adoption and helping to save a life!
 

Please visit us online at www.DogsXLRescue.org

animal.description:
RHUMBA - 4 years old, 50 pounds, house trained, great with adults and children, no other pets, playful, active, will go after other dogs when they walk by,

Rhumba aka Callie has been in and out of the Virginia Beach Animal Care and Adoption Center several times. Her perfect family seems elusive up to this point but we are sure the perfect match is still out there. Rhumba is a sweet and friendly girl. She loves humans, old and young. She is great with humans, loves attention, loves to play, and loves to be near her humans. She does not, however, like other animals. On a walk, she will bark and try her best to get at other dogs if she sees them. She will need a family ready and prepared to hold her tight when another dog walks or runs by. Management is key in situations like this. Rhumba should remain at a distance where she holds her focus on you, not the other dog. You, as her owner, will have to be prepared to find that certain distance from where Rhumba's focus remains on you and not the other animal. Treats help and with her round belly, it's clear she is motivated by treats! Daily walks and/or runs would do her good, again realizing that you'll have to manage her behavior if you see another dog. Other than that, Rhumba is a loving and carefree girl who just wants to be at her humans' side. She's waiting at the Virginia Beach Animal Care and Adoption Center. Call us at 385-4444 or go to our Facebook page to make an appointment to meet her. We are located at 341 S Birdneck Road and are open daily except for Tuesdays.

animal.description:
Our Buttercup is looking for a FUR-EVER home! 

She is about 2 years old and is a pittie!  She is the biggest baby with nothing but love to give. She came to us covered in scars and you could tell she had been bred multiple times. From the looks of how she came in, we assume she was a breeder dog that spent most of her life (if not all) in a kennel to pop out litters when wanted. How she became a stray, we have no idea. Her legs are still scarred up but she has no issues. She loves anything and everything. She definitely has a momma personality. 

Please give this girl a shot. She has a bark that can sound mean but she has a heart of GOLD. She loves belly rubs and dragging her tummy across the grass. She wants to be in your lap and hasn’t figured out that she isn’t a small dog. She adores kids and other dogs. She would probably be good with cats (she just hasn’t been tested yet). 

She isn’t flashy but she is full of love and we think that is even better!!

Give us a call or send us a message and let’s set up a meet and greet today!! You won’t regret it!

animal.description:
Hatchi has it all: good looks, is affectionate, and ready for an adventure at any time! Hatchi is a great contender for agility or trick training as he loves having a job and pleasing his humans. He does great meeting new people and has never met a stranger. Hatchi does well with other dogs after proper introductions though he would also enjoy a home as an only dog where the focus is entirely on him! Hatchi loves the car, peanut butter, chewing on deer antlers, being brushed and following his humans around the house. There’s not much he doesn’t like apart from hands near his food. This young Pyr craves human attention and is looking for humans that can provide him structure and help correct him when he gets over excited and mouthy when playing (he has some basic training and takes correction well). Hatchi will do best in a home with older children that understand how to reinforce good behavior. Hatchi’s Pyrfect family has the time to spend with him going for walks and keeping his mind active and focused so he can live up to his full potential! Most of all, he’s looking for that special human that wants to hang out all the time and give him all the love and attention he craves. If Hatchi sounds like the right fit for your family, apply for this fun-loving boy today!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

*FOSTER OR ADOPTER NEEDED ASAP*

This boy with the handsome profile is Harley.  Although we currently only have this one picture of him, we can still tell that he’s a looker!  Harley is about 2 ½ years-old and his dad, sadly, passed away recently.  Harley is now in need of a new home and we’re hoping to help him find just that!

Harley has been staying with his late dad’s friends, but they have no experience with dogs and realize that they’re just not the right home for him.  The family isn’t sure how Harley does with strangers, kids, or dogs, but they do know that he likes to go after small animals and he’s a strong, excited pup, so he’ll need an experienced family who can help him learn boundaries and appropriate socialization skills. 

Please help us get sweet Harley into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!

animal.description:
Hey friends! I'm Damon and I am a 3 year old terrier mix. Like many others looking for love I have some baggage from my past. I spent the first years of my life outside with many other dogs and little human attention. Because of this it takes me a little while to trust people and new dogs. I have been with my foster mom now for a couple months and am starting to really show her who I am. I have learned it is ok to share my space and toys with other dogs. I really like to run around and play with dogs who are a little bigger with me who have energy. Once I am done playing I like to nap on the couch cuddled up with foster mom. I walk well on leash and stick next to foster mom checking in with her throughout the walk. Some of my favorite things are food, eating fresh snow, playing with toys and barking at animals and people outside. Foster mom says I am still working on learning some of the basics but that I am a really sweet and fun boy. My foster family has helped me learn what it is like to be loved and part of a family and I am ready to find my forever home. Could it be you?

If you would like to meet Damon please complete an online application that can be found at: http://hopeanimalrescueofiowa.org/forms/196/dog-application

Adoption fee is $250 which includes spay/neuter, age-appropriate vaccines/tests, and microchip.

animal.description:
FROM THE FOSTER: I wanted to give you a quick update on Chip. He is doing very well and is a pleasure to have around the house. He is the perfect child - seen, but not heard when people have been in the house. He investigates, says hello and then goes and lies under the kitchen table or in his kennel.

He is good when we go outside and will always go to the bathroom. He drank a lot of water one day and he wanted to go outside to pee about 2 hours after he had been out, so he went and stood by the door and kept looking at me to be let out. He is smart. My cat is used to having a dog around so she just stepped in and took over, proceeding to snuggle into Chips bed. He was a bit afraid of her at first, but now they are buddies and sleep close to each other; he under the kitchen table on the rug and she close by in the chair.

We have been going for short walks. He starts out perky and is excited to go out, but by the time we get back, he is walking slower and behind me. He may be getting tired because he is moving his whole body when he walks, not just his legs, although he is never panting, but, out in the backyard, when he has just gone outside, if there is a squirrel around, he will chase it. Thats all for now on our boy. He is a good dog!

ORIGINAL POST: Chip is a six (6) year old lab mix who was picked up wandering on the side of the road and taken to a shelter. He has a neurological issue that impairs his ability to walk normally. In addition, he came in with a large stick wedged between his upper teeth that grew into the roof of his mouth and punctured his nasal cavity. Hes been treated by an oral surgeon and everything is fine now, but his bill was close to $10,000 and we still have a $3,000 MRI to diagnose his neurological issue. Luckily, Chip has a wonderful foster who is committed to seeing him through all of his treatment, which Chip has handled like a champ with a smile on his face. If you would like to foster to adopt Chip, please go to www.atlantalabrescue.com to fill out an application.

animal.description:
Melvin is a nearly 2-year old, adorable Pit Bull Terrier who was scheduled for euthanasia in a St. Joe shelter before Muddy Paws saved him. He is very sweet, has a goofy personality, and loves to cuddle. Playing with children makes Melvin happy so he hopes for some kids in his new home. He enjoys playing fetch and going for walks. He is a fast learner and has learned several commands while in his foster home. He is housetrained and crate trained. A home without other pets would be best for Melvin. He is very reactive to male dogs.

Before applying to adopt this dog, you need to be familiar with your local breed-specific legislation regarding Pit Bulls. 

The suggested adoption donation for Melvin is $300. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.All of the animals posted on our site have been temperament tested. While not all are in the immediate area, once we have processed and approved your application, we will move the dog to our adoptive area for you to meet, greet and hopefully adopt. Sometimes we will have more than one application on a dog. That does not mean it automatically goes to another family but you should be aware of the fact that until you are approved and set up for the meet/greet.. the dog could get adopted by another applicant.

Gazing into Kae's soulful amber eyes tells you without words that she is an old soul restored to a vital body. One meaning for 'Kae' is 'keeper of the keys' and having known her for a little while, she has already started gathering the keys to her caregivers' hearts, so we are certain she will collect and treasure the keys to her forever family's hearts quickly as well!

Kae's photo shows her offering the excellent eye contact so important to training success. This focus combined with her eager to please attitude, and all you will need to add are the best possible treats in the whole wide world. Then the sky will be your limit when continuing to build her skills together.

Kae will enjoy a hike on the trail as much as a quiet afternoon lounging in her sunny back yard. She's not one for the hustle and bustle of city life and will thrive on the predictable routines others might find a tad, well, almost boring.

Kae has a foundation of basic obedience, beginning exposure to agility, early leash skills (tempered by youthful enthusiasm); she is crate trained and housebroken.

Kae would prefer a forever home with a private back yard so she can run and play to her heart's content and rest with limited distractions. Kae can be environmentally sensitive to some loud sounds. If you are interested in learning more details about Kae, please contact:
rorrcanine@gmail.com

animal.description: Ivan is a very sweet boy who didn't have the easiest start to life. When he came to Labs and More he was very sick and never received proper puppy socialization. Now he is 100% better and is single and ready to mingle! Around 7 months old, Ivan is likely a Lab mix and he's currently on track to be a big dog when he's done growing! He is shy and wary with new people and will need a family that recognizes it will take a little time and patience to help him settle in. However once he does, he becomes a happy, silly boy that loves to romp and play. Ivan is fostered with several other dogs and does great with them. Due to his size and typical puppy rambunctiousness when playing, he can be a little much for the smaller, less active dogs in his foster home so he would love a home with an equally playful dog sibling. He enjoys playing with tug toys and running around the yard. He bonds closely with his people and likes to crawl up in his foster mom's lap for attention. He will need a family that continues to work on socialization and training with him so he can be the best boy he can be. Ivan is looking for a family that understands the time, patience, and energy needed to raise a young pup. We require all puppy adopters to provide training that includes: house training, basic training, leash training, and socialization. Additionally, this cutie is going to need proper exercise, mental stimulation, and your attention and love to grow up to be the best companion. We do not allow our dogs or puppies to sleep or live outside; they must be incorporated into your family and be made a priority in your life. In return, you will have the most loving and loyal family member you could ask for. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Ivan, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Meet gorgeous Zara!  This beautiful girl was found dragging her legs on a desert road.  She was hit by a car most likely.  She had a fracture in both legs one at the hip and the other at the knee.  Zara has had orthopedic surgery and has fully recovered.  She runs and plays like any other dog her age. You would never guess she ever had a fracture.  It's so wonderful to see a pup that couldn't walk, running around like all dogs her age. She is likely around 8 to 10 months now and ready for her forever home.  She will be spayed prior to finalizing an adoption, microchipped and vaccinated.  

Zara is in a foster home with other dogs and she gets along with small and large breeds. She is not good with cats! She weighs around 50 to 55lbs and we believe she is near her adult size.  She is house broken and lets you know when she needs to go out.  She is a pup so she will need exercise and chew toys.

If you are interested in this gorgeous girl, please email us some information about your household and experience with pets.  

Thank you for considering Zara to be part of your family.

animal.description:
Meet Tioga!  He's an energetic younger adult Husky type boy!  Tioga is good-natured, fun and ready for adventure!  He knows how to "sit" and is gentle with food.  He doesn't seem so interested in toys, but wants to romp and play with humans and seems to want to play with our other dogs!  The person who found him kept him for several days, hoping to find his owner.  There was an older dog with health issues in the home, and Tioga's energy level  was a little too much for the other dog, so Tioga is currently housed at Del Norte Animal Control, waiting for a new home!  Tioga can be pretty vocal when he wants attention, and when put into an enclosure, his first order of business is to check the perimeter to see if there are any weaknesses, so he will need a secure environment.  Tioga has a great personality and is ready for fresh start in a new home!
Come check out Tioga and our other dogs available for adoption at 2650 Washington Blvd, Crescent City, CA 95531.

Please call us at (707) 464-7235 for additional information.  More photos of this dog may be available on the Dogs of Del Norte County Facebook page.

animal.description:
Scroll down to learn more about this pet:

***
Bichon and Little Buddies is open only

by appointment with a completed application.
Dogs in foster homes require an appointment and approved application to meet. The application is online at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog If a dog is listed as available, then we are still taking applications - no need to email or call to ask about the status. Note: The forms that Petfinder or Adopt-a-pet has to inquire about the dog is not our application application. Our form must be filled out to be approved to adopt a pet.***

Covid-19 Precautions:

Until further notice, Bichon & Little Buddies will be doing all meets and adoptions by appointment only. To be able to control the number of people at the shelter at one time, we will be suspending our open hours on Thursdays. If interested in adopting, please fill out the pre-adoption application and we will set up a time for you to come meet the dogs you are interested in.

About this Dog:

Name: Dakota

Breed: Mixed

Approximate Age: 4-5 months

Gender: Female

Weight: 20 lb

Adoption Fee: $475

Why in Rescue: Transfer from Texas

General Profile: Please fill out the adoption application at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog if you are interested in meeting one of our dogs.

Dakota came from Texas hoping to find a wonderful home in Wisconsin. While she was scared at first, she is a happy girl now. We don't have a history on her, so don't know if she has been working on housetraining or how she is with children. We don't know her mix, her paperwork says Boxer mix, but we don't really see that other than her super cute underbite. Many of the dogs from Texas are true mixed breeds - a little of this and a little of that, and that is most likely what Dakota is. If interested in meeting Dakota, please fill out the pre-adoption application and we will let you know if you are approved to meet her.

We do our best to evaluate the dogs while they are with us, but they sometimes act different in the shelter environment than they do in a home. If you are interested in any of our dogs, please fill out the pre-adoption application and we will set up a time for you to come and meet them.

Adoption Procedures:

1. Completely fill out the pre-adoption application at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog. We will be checking with your vet if you have had pets, calling your landlord (if any) and checking a personal reference, before we contact you about visiting the adoptables. Any missing information may have us moving onto another application.

2. If you application is approved, we will contact you to come meet the adoptables that you are interested in.

3. If it is a match, you will complete the adoption contract and pay the adoption fee. Please be prepared to take your adopted pet home when you come meet him/her. In most cases, you will be able to take the pet home the same day. If all the vetting hasn't been done yet, we will hold the pet for you until the vet work is completed.

4. If you have filled out an application and we haven't contacted you within a week, we may have missed your application, the pet may have been adopted by another applicant, or you may have been missing information on your application. You may contact us to find out the status of your application at this time. Please give us a week to process your application before contacting us!

The adoption fee through Bichon and Little Buddies Rescue is $200 - $475 depending on the age of the dog, which includes Wi State Sales Tax. Included in this fee is your new companion who will be spayed/neutered, have a current Certificate of Veterinary Inspection (as required by state law), current on age appropriate vaccinations, heartworm tested and started on preventative, microchipped, and dewormed. Other medical needs will also have been taken care of, such as dentals and treating ear infections.

To assist you and your new pet in adjusting to life together, you will also receive an 8 week age appropriate obedience training course at For Pet's Sake Dog Training for $50 (up to $200 value). You may opt to take Puppy Kindergarten, Adult Beginners, Small Dogs Big Hearts, or Shy & Reactive Dog Class. You must start the class within 90 days of adoption for the reduced fee. For more information on the classes visit www.forpetssake.cc

All dogs are seen BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. Many are in various foster homes getting extra one on one attention getting them ready for their new homes. The first step in adoption is filling out the pre-adoption application. Bichon and Little Buddies is run by volunteers who have full time jobs in addition to the hours they spend with the rescue dogs. Having an application on file assures us that the potential adopter is really interested in adopting a dog. It also assists us in placing dogs in homes where both the dog and new owners are happy. The application puts you under no obligation to adopt a dog from Bichon and Little Buddies.

The Dog Pre-Adoption Application can be found at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog

Thanks for thinking about adopting your new pet!More important information:

***We are a Wisconsin based rescue and do not ship our pets. If you are considering adoption you must be willing to drive to meet and adopt the pet, as well as bring the pet back to us if the adoption doesn't work. We adopt primarily in WI and IL, but will consider applicants in MN, IA, and MI.***

***Please do not set up an appointment to meet the animals until you are ready to take your pet home. If the meeting results in a match, you can often take the dog/cat home the same day or within a couple days if the medical care hasn't been completed. We are not able to hold pets for adopters beyond this time. Thanks for understanding.***

***While we hope all of our adoptions lead to permanent homes for the animals we place, sometimes things just don't work out. We do have a 30 day trial period. For the first 30 days, if you or Bichon and Little Buddies decide that the adoption isn't a good match for either the humans or the pet, the adoption fee will be refunded minus $50 within 30 days of the return of the dog. Bichon and Little Buddies also requires adopters to return the pet to us at any time that they are unable or unwilling to care for the animal anymore.***

***We do not show dogs/cats without an appointment. The first step in adoption is filling out the pre-adoption application at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog Please do not call/email until AFTER you have filled out an application.***

Bichon and Little Buddies is a State Licensed Rescue # 268555-DS

animal.description:
Meet Bryce,
Bryce is the cutest little red boy you will ever meet. Bryce is looking for the perfect adopter that will work with him. He is between 10-14 months old but life thus far hasn't done him any justice. Bryce needs to be in a home with older children and a home that doesn't have a lot of visitors as he is protective of his family. Bryce shouldn't be with small animals and would be best with as an only dog or with potentially a submissive female. His current trainer will include training sessions with his adopter to continue on his improvements but needs that special someone who is willing to love him and give him the life that he deserves. He overall is a great boy just needs a savvy doberman owner to understand him! 
Training will be mandatory with the trainer that Bryce did board and train with. An appointment must be setup and kept with his trainer in the Denver area. 

All animals adopted from us are fully vetted including spay/neuter, vaccines, microchip, heartworm test and deworming. Please email us at HookedOnDobies@gmail.com, visit our Facebook page www.facebook.com/savingdobermankind or webpage https://www.savingdobermankind.org to request an application, inquire about an adoption fee, or to learn more! 

We do require a completed adoption application to be submitted before discussing details of a specific Doberman. 

We DO NOT have a central location, out foster homes are located throughout our geographic region including CO, WY, NM and TX.

We strive to PROTECT the privacy of out fosters. ALL Doberman meet and greets are conducted in a neutral meeting location made by appointment only.

animal.description:
Meet Willow! 

Fox and Willow are neutered  male and spayed  female 1 year old Australian Shepherd mixes (per paperwork). We have determined them to be a bonded pair that should be adopted together. They came from a not so great past which causes them to be timid and a bit shy at first. The great thing is, they are still so sweet. They  want to trust humans, they  really do. They will let you carry them, pet them and hang out next to them.  They feel very comfortable around dogs. They are  content laying with them and watching all that goes on in a new place. They are crate trained and are very quiet dogs. Fox and Willow are beautiful and the perfect size for most households. Since they do need a patient beginning, apply for them because you are that home not because they are  gorgeous. A fenced yard is required for them. Fox and Willow don't like a leash much right now probably because we were told that their family was  dragged into animal control by their necks. Its amazing that Fox and Willow  still want to trust people, but they do. They are  going to be the best dogs for a lucky person, couple  or family.  Apply if you think you are their  match. ? You won't be disappointed...these dogs are  special.

Interested in meeting Willow? 

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Age appropriate vaccinations
- Heartworm test (for dogs over 6mo) and treatment if positive
- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

*Please note that the identified breed(s) are best guesses. We very rarely have information on our dogs' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays.*

6yo neutered male 58lbs

Loving, Silly, Curious

Meet Roux (pronounced Roo). He is the perfect age of 6yrs young and petite at 58lbs. When you meet him you are instantly in love with his sweet face, likely due to his large overbite - or tiny chin. He likes to be close at all times, and will even give you a nudge for a pet or just simply sit in front of you so he can stare at you lovingly. Inside the house, Roux loves to relax and when outside he is curious and loves to sniff around. He is dog social with calm dogs matching his energy level. He is currently in training with our guys in our Prison Training Program, brushing up on his crate training and house training. If you're looking for a chill best friend, Roux is your boy!

animal.description:
{s3829code380/}
If you would like to provide this dog a loving home, please fill out a pre-adoption application.

Have a question? Please read our Frequently Asked Questions and Adoption Processed Explained documentation.
_________ B I O ______________

Name:Susie Q
Size: ~Medium range: 26-60 lbs
Adoption Donation:$250 (applicable sales tax included).Adoption fees may be paid by cash or check.
Other:Spayed Female, Vaccinations current, Microchip

**
Susie Q is a three-legged dog (tri-paw'd). To understand how to help, view this link: https://www.thesprucepets.com/three-legged-dogs-4177794

Susie Qis such a sweet girl!

Foster Home Feedback

1/23/21: Susie Q has made so much progress in the last month! She has potty training down, and she hasn't had an accident inside in weeks. She also sleeps through the night and goes to the bathroom right away when we let her out in the morning.

She can be very energetic and playful, and it has helped her to have our dog as a playmate. They do get rough at times! She loves playing with toys as well. When calm, she loves to sleep on her dog bed or cuddles up next to one of us. Susie Q is a big cuddler. When new people come over, she does tend to get very energetic and barks, but does calm down after a while and does fine. We have had a few kids over and Susie Q does fine with them. She has started to nip a little bit when she gets excited or wants to play, so we are working on that.

Overall, we still really enjoy having Susie Q. She is a great companion and loves being around people! I think she would benefit from another dog playmate as well.

12/13/2020: Susie Q has been with us for a few weeks now, and she has definitely made some progress! She now goes up and down the stairs with no issues. Our current dog and Susie Q still get along really well and love to play together. She has gotten more used to our cat and leaves her alone most of the time. We go on walks daily and she does dart around a little bit but has started to get the hang of it. She is becoming more independent and loves chewing on bones/kongs with frozen peanut butter.

We are still working on potty training with Susie. She does well during the day when we are home because we take her out every couple of hours. We are working on crate training her when we are at work. She has had a few accidents while we are gone, but she sleeps most of the day and doesn't get into anything. She sleeps in our room at night, and we still have to take her out a couple of times a night.

Overall, Susie Q is such a lover and loves any and all attention! She has been a fun dog to have around and would love a home with a dog to play with and lots of time and attention to give.

12/2/2020: Susie Q has been such a fun dog! She gets along really well with our current dog. They love to play together, even with only 3 legs, she sure keeps up! She shows a lot of interest in our cat and wants to play with her, but she is easily redirected away from her.

Susie Q loves to cuddle and be around her humans. She can be calm and cuddly a lot of the time, but she still does have puppy energy and loves to run around play. She likes to play with squeaky toys and tug-of-war. She also does well on walks. Susie Q was struggling with going up the stairs for the first week due to only having 3 legs. With some practice and help from us, she is starting to get the hang of it and has gone up the stairs all by herself a few times!

11/14/2020: Susie Q is very sweet and loving. She loves attention. We are working on kennel training and potty training. She has a bit of separation anxiety and needs someone who can be patient with her. Susie Q is an amazing dog and perfect for any family. To view additional dogs available for adoption, please see our website: www.4luvofdog.org

animal.description:
Charlotte is a senior GSD Mix. She is wonderful with people and children. She is very soft mouthed when taking treats and does not nip.  She is perfectly house broken and will let you know when she needs to go out. She knows sit, down, the hand signal for lay down, and paw (shake).  

For her age, she is in excellent health.  Still wants to play ball, or just sleep with it him her mouth.  She is also a great couch potato if you want to snuggle up.  Charlotte needs to be the only pet in the house. She has gotten along with other dogs her size. Her last buddy a Pitbull boxer mix was adopted, and her other friend, a female St Bernard passed of cancer.  She initially did not take well to the ST Bernard coming to the house, but after a few short interactions, she was good friends with her.  She cannot be with small animals, because like many other breeds, she does have prey drive.  She is not good with cats or small dogs.  She is 12 years old. We believe she still has several years ahead of her. She is still playful and strong loves her toys.  Her teeth are in excellent shape and aside from being a bit stiff when initially getting up, she gets around well.  She can still run, and is not in anyway having mobility issues other than stiffness initially (kinda like me) :).  

This girl is super sweet and affectionate and has lived with small children with no issues at all.

animal.description:
My name is Phoenix. I have been with my foster dad for 7 months! I really love him, but I really need a Furever home. I am a Great Pyrenees/Lab mix who came from Needy Paws Animal Shelter in Arkansas where I was surrendered with my two brothers because of a family illness. Some of my attributes are: I'm friendly and social, love people, affectionate, playful, and gentle. I greet my foster dad by jumping onto my dog house, putting my paws on his shoulders, and giving him a hug! I like water, playing with other dogs, am house trained, and I don't pull on a leash. For a 7-8 year old, I still really enjoys my walks and require them. I would do best in a rural setting as I've lived my whole life on a farm with other dogs. I don't like to share my food with other dogs so I need my own space to eat. My foster dad has not seen me around cats. I weigh about 60 lbs, and will come to you neutered, up to date on vaccinations, up to date on heartworm and flea/tick preventatives, and microchipped.

animal.description:
Senior Hearts Rescue and Renewal is the only licensed senior dog rescue organization in Western Pennsylvania. We do not have a shelter or a public facility. ALL of our dogs reside in foster homes in the greater Pittsburgh, PA area. 

We are a 100% volunteer organization. Please respect our volunteers' time. If a dog is listed on PetFinder, he/she IS available for adoption. We cannot reply to messages, phone calls, and emails about a dog until we have received, reviewed, and approved an adoption application. 

Our ADOPTION application is found at www.seniorhearts.org Completing this application is the first step in our adoption screening process. You MUST complete the application in entirety in order to be considered as a potential adopter.  Please select "More About Us" for further details on our adoption requirements.  You can meet a dog ONLY after we have completed our adoption approval process.

If you are looking at the dog below, it most certainly means the dog is available for adoption. We look forward to receiving your application in hopes that you are able to meet our adoption requirements and provide this dog a loving furever home.

Hi everyone. I’m officially ready to find my furever home. I do have a few requirements. I need sunglasses, a fenced yard, and a doggie sibling. If you don’t have those, I’m not the guy for you. 
I’m 9yrs going and weigh 12lbs. 

I’m a friendly boy who enjoys exploring the great outdoors and going on short walks. Exercise is very important for me because it helps me stay strong and maintain my athletic build. I have some congenital issues with my front legs. I used to fall over all the time. But my Senior Hearts foster parents helped me get slim and strong so I hardly ever fall over anymore. 

I have to be honest about one thing. I snore a lot. And it’s very loud. Sometimes it sounds like a piggy snorting. If you want to give me a furever home, you have to appreciate loud dog snoring. 

I like to sit in laps for for those zoom meetings and Netflix binge watching. I am crate trained and sleep like a good boy all night in my crate and when the humans leave the home. 

I like spending time with other dogs. But I only like dogs close to my size and dogs that aren’t too rambunctious or too pushy. I can be bossy and tell off a dog that gets in my face too much. 

I don’t want children in my home. I think they would tire me. I can be adopted within a two hour radius of Pittsburgh, PA. If you want to meet me you must first complete the adoption application at www.seniorhearts.org
xoxoxo Ricky

animal.description:
Good With Kids: Older kids
Good With Other Dogs: Yes
Good With Cats:  Unknown
Housetrained:  Yes
Crate Trained:  Yes
Walks Nicely On A Leash:  Working on it
Knows Basic Commands:  Yes
Energy Level (Couch Potato, Moderate or High):  Moderate to high
Special Needs: May require medication for pain management due to two hip fractures that will likely become arthritic later in life
Physical Fence: Required

No Invisible Fences, Please

Arrival story:  Cassie came to us from Detroit Animal Care & Control when a plea was put out for someone to transport her to the vet after it was suspected she had been hit by a car

Approximate age / Weight:  9 mths/28 lbs

Personality: Our sweet baby girl, Cassie, had a rough start to her puppyhood. She arrived at the shelter after being hit by a car, and the ER vet determined she had 2 hip fractures that would require surgery and a long road to recovery. Now almost 5 months later, Cassie is completely off activity restriction and thriving. She is a fun-loving girl who wants to play with the other dogs in her foster home, run around in the yard, go for car rides, or chew on a nylabone or a peanut butter kong. When she’s not romping around, Cassie insists on being a lap dog. Cassie is a very snuggly girl who wants to be curled up in bed with you or sleeping on your legs during tv time. She will settle down nicely once she’s been given appropriate outlets for her puppy energy and will quietly chew on her toys. 

Cassie enjoys walks on hiking trails or in fields, but being around traffic makes her very anxious. Because she was on activity restriction for so long, she's just now beginning work on her leash skills. 

Cassie is crate trained, but has been left out for a few hours at a time and does fine. If crated, she prefers to be in the same room as the other dogs.  She plays nicely with other playful dogs, but can sometimes make a nuisance of herself with dogs who don't want to partake in playtime.   Although Cassie likes almost everyone she meets, she can be shy at first and needs slow introductions. Overall, Cassie is just a fun and playful pup ready to put the past behind her and move forward with a family to call her own

Forever home: Cassie is looking for a home with an active family that will give her all the love and attention she deserves, especially after everything she’s been through. Ideally, she wouldn’t have to be left alone often, and her family would be able to invest in her continued training and socialization.  She will do best with a playful canine companion.  Because of Cassie’s injuries, her doctors said she will have arthritis when she’s older, so having her on medication for pain management in the future is likely. Cassie requires a physically fenced yard so she can run freely and burn off her puppy energy safely.


If you are interested in meeting a dog, please complete the Adoption Application on our website, www.waggintailsdogrescue.org>Adopt>Adoption Application.
 
ADOPTION INFO:
 
We do not have a facility; all of our dogs are fostered in private homes.   We generally have two adoption events per month.  To meet a dog in person, please see our event calendar on our website for the date and time of the next adoption event. Arrangements can be made to meet a dog outside of Saturday adoption events after an application is submitted and approved.

Our adoption process includes an application and in-home meet-n-greet with the dog.

Applications will be considered for the Southeast Michigan area.

We do not do out of state adoptions.

-Adult Dog Adoption Fee - $225
-Small Breed Adoption Fee - $275
-Senior Dog Adoption Fee - $125
-Pup Adoption Fee - $250 plus $50 spay/neuter deposit refunded upon proof of surgery by 6 mos.
 
Thank you for supporting dog rescue and your interest in a rescue dog!
