animal.description:
Courtesy Listing!
Courtesy dog listing, please direct all inquiries to the information provided within the bio below (CBCR does not warranty any information provided about courtesy dogs listed)

About Ollie:

Sex: Male
Age: 5 years old
Coat: Black and white, medium length
Weight: 65 lbs
Activity Level: Active Pet
House Trained, Neutered, Current on Vaccination

Biography
I rescued Ollie from a local animal shelter in February 2016. At that time he had been taken in as a stray and appeared to have been attacked as he had a hematoma on his chest and drains in his legs from the wounds. He still looked so happy even though he’d been through so much. I took my now 13 y/o beagle mix to meet him at the shelter and they’ve been buddies ever since. After adopting Ollie, he was heartworm positive so I treated him and then had him neutered. Pre-neuter he would jump my small fence in backyard but not after. He is not much of a barker but will bark if something goes bump in the night. He’s anxious and likes to chomp on lacrosse balls which are indestructible. He likes walks on the leash but pulls a lot. He becomes anxious when seeing another dog on a walk and is sometimes hard to control. He would do great with a lot of land or a fenced in yard. He has never chewed up things in my house. He and my beagle eat from same bowl. Ollie likes being boarded with his beagle sister and plays well with other dogs at playtime outside-mainly older dogs. He bit my friend’s dog about 6 months ago when we introduced them on leashes. Her dog was an energetic shepherd mix with a loud bark. I recently moved to dog friendly apartment complex. He enjoys walks but is still anxious around the dogs. This morning Ollie nipped and broke skin on my neighbors arm when she reached out to pet him. He has never bitten me or any child but I cannot take a chance on him doing that here. Ollie likes attention but he is not a lap dog. He sleeps in the living room during night. He enjoys looking out window and sleeping during day.

Does the dog have any history of aggression such as growling, lunging, snapping or biting any adult or child?
Yes

Please explain the aggression toward people.
Has never been aggressive toward any guests or children in my home. History of one bite/nip on arm as described above.

Does the dog have any history of aggression toward other animals?
Yes

Please explain the aggression toward other animals.
Does not like cats. Ollie has history of being attacked and will fight for himself if necessary.

Reason for re-homing?
Potential risk to other residents now living in close proximity to me.

Location & Contact
Ollie is located in Bermuda Run NC.  For more information, reach out to April at agstaley90@gmail.com or 336-403-6383.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Glory. I was left at the Yucca Valley Animal Shelter as a stray. Unfortunately, nobody came to claim me during my stray hold. During my stay at that shelter, I was very timid and fearful, so nobody was interested in adopting me. The staff of the shelter called to ask if this shelter could take me in so I would have a better chance of being adopted. Luckily, they had plenty of space and agreed to take me in. It has taken a little time, but I have come around and the staff has been able to see more of my personality. I am very relaxed and calm, and I just enjoy laying around napping, and going out to sun bathe in the yard. I would love to find a calm and loving home where I can just lounge around and relax, enjoying the good life I deserve. I get along pretty well with other dogs, but the staff is not sure how I will do with cats. I will be temperament tested with cats during my stay here, so if you have cats and are interested in adopting me, please ask staff if I have been evaluated with them yet. If you have any questions, or if you would like to come up to visit with me, please ask staff.
                                                                                   Love,
                                                                                     Glory

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Gretta, I was transferred to this shelter from a public shelter because I had been there for quite a while, and nobody was interested in adopting me during my stay there. Luckily for me, the staff of the shelter knew that I deserved more time to find my furever home, so they contacted this shelter and got me in. I am very sweet and loving, and I love to get lots of attention and go out on walks. I can be a little bratty with other dogs, but I do get along with some. I prefer males over females, but my real issue with other dogs is that I do not like alpha dogs. I might be a senior, but I am still very active and love to go out on walks and spend time with people. I have allergies, so I am on a special diet (Purina Pro Plan Sensitive Skin & Stomach), but I LOVE food! Since I have allergies, it would be best for me to go into a home with a family who can afford my special food, and will take my allergies seriously, and not give me human food and other foods that will trigger my allergies (no matter how much I beg). I have not been temperament tested with cats yet, but the staff will see how I do while I am here. If you would like to meet me outside of my kennel, or if you have any questions, please ask staff.
                                                                                                 Love,
                                                                                                Gretta

animal.description: Panda #7160 is a beautiful 5-year-old female Border Collie mix.  Panda is very sweet, and she adapts easily to a new home. She is well behaved, affectionate, calm. She is house trained. She enjoys running around the yard, and is good with her foster family's  dog. She is happy to sit next to you and get scratches. She likes to find "her" spot and settle in, perhaps on a particular corner of the couch. Panda sleeps well in the crate and sleeps all night. She is great in the car. She appreciates treats but does not beg. Panda is the perfect little companion dog. Panda is an LCAR momma who came to us with Heartworms.  She was great mom to her pups and is ready for some R&R before she begins her Heartworm treatment. Panda is seeking an adopter/foster who will be able to continue LCAR’s provided Heartworm treatment. She weighs 45 pounds and is full grown. If you are interested in fostering to adopt this pup, AND are already approved to adopt through our organization, please contact dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with the pup’s name and ID number in the subject line. OTHERWISE, please submit an adoption application online: http://www.lastchanceanimalrescue.org/adoptus.html. Keep in mind it takes 1-2 weeks for applications to be processed.  E-mail dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with questions. Stay tuned to our Facebook page for updates: Last Chance Animal Rescue #adoptlove #PicMe #petsmartcharities

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Connor came to us in pretty rough shape. However, we are working each day with this snuggle bug to get him healthy and find the perfect person to keep up his foster family's healing work. Is that person you?

Connor is a 8 year old German Shepherd mix with the most beautiful smile. His favorite past times are snuggling with his person or feeling the cool breeze go through his fur. He would be the perfect friend for a low energy person or family and be a champion at Netflix marathons!

Connor has osteoarthritis and spondylosis. This means he has extreme arthritis and disk problems in his spine. Connor is walking well and improving each day as we dial in his pain medication. He loves low energy activities such as moving with his person from room to room, or supervising while you putter in the yard.

Connor has not been receptive to other dogs so far, so he may be best in a home without other dogs. While he is a sweetie, we also do not recommend small children. He is not always steady on his feet, and if they start pulling on him, he may snap at them out of fear. He has been great with older, respectful children. Connor has no food aggression or allergies issues. He is on pain medication and we continue to work with our vet to get the exact doses right.

While Connor is in his senior years, we are confident that with the right family, this guy will really shine. Connor would love to talk to someone about couch snuggles today!

Ps - he gives the sweetest kisses!

Nuts and Bolts: 8 years old, male, soon to be neutered, 60lbs, no cats, unsure about dogs, older kids only, no steps, needs training, does not need a fenced yardIf you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

animal.description:
Looks like: Australian Shepherd
Male, 12 years old, 30 pounds

Remmy is a sweet older gentleman. He is apprehensive at first and does not like to be lifted. He does snap at too forward people and so should go to a home without children and be with understanding adopters. He has quite an impressive resume otherwise -- he is great with big or small dogs and cats. He is crate trained and rides well in the car. He is a bit on the timid side at first and prefers to be left untouched until he gets used to you. He isn't described as overly affectionate with people but will warm up to you once he trusts you. 

Remmy did not go many places before coming to POMDR. So a walk to a busy place can be very overwhelming. He has lived a reserved life and it shows in his personality. Slow exposure is ideal for him. 

He walks well on leash. He eats and sleeps in his crate - being led in by food and then settling in comfortably. Remmy does pace in the house and yard, especially during transition but then will mostly just follow his person around. He wants to be with you and is actually showing anxiety when left behind so needs help understanding being left alone is ok. He is hearing and vision impaired but has good energy for his age. He listens well but doesn't really know any commands. 

Remmy came to us from the Newman Animal Shelter.

animal.description:
"Why, hello there! Thanks for visiting me online! My name is Booker and  I’m a new arrival to Providence Animal Center from Arkansas. My litter mates and myself were found on the side of the road in a kennel, so can we both agree that I can’t wait to move from here into my new forever home. 

The staff feel that the right forever home for me will have another confident doggie roommate with a fully fenced in yard. Since I'm still learning about how wonderful everything in life can be, my ideal home will be in a quiet setting and calm inside - no city/apartment life or wild parties for me!  If you have children, kids 12+ would be great. I'd also likely do well living with a kitty friend!

I'm been staying with one of PAC's fabulous fosters and they have the following to say about me:

"He's really coming out of his shell. He prefers the company of another dog, but will come to people he trusts for pets and cuddles. For potential adopters: fully housebroken, never barks, loves chew toys and bones. He loves to run and wrestle with my dog. We are working on leash skills as he is still a bit shy about fast movements and loud sounds."

So what do you say? I promise we will be best buds. Please send your completed adoption profile (found here:https://providenceac.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Adoption-Profile.pdf) to foster@providenceac.org. My paws are crossed. 

XO - Booker

P.S. I'm a little over 1 year old, 47 pounds, neutered, microchipped and up to date on all my vaccinations."

P.S. S. A generous donor is eager to help me find my forever home, so they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! YAY!

Some of this pet's photos have been provided by Crissy Everhart Photography 

___

Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. To find out this pet’s adoption fee or for more information, please call the Adoption Center with this pet’s ID number.

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

animal.description:
Who is the tiniest but the mightiest?? Well Hercules of course!! 

Hercules is a 13 year old Lhasa Apso Poodle mix! This handsome guy has been adjusting well in his new foster home, and has been warming up to everyone!! He really just likes to be held, (all 9 whole pounds of him) and cuddled up with his foster Dad most of the time. He also loves to curl up on his foster Dad's shoulder when laying on the couch or in the bed. Hercules does have cushings disease, but is not showing any signs or any issues. His Adopter will have to look for any signs of cushings in the future. He does not currently need on any medication for this.

His perfect furever home would be a home where he can be that lucky someone's nap companion and relax most of the day. Maybe go for an afternoon stroll to explore and smell the fresh air, and then an evening filled with belly rubs and A+ cuddling.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Jilly. I was transferred from a public shelter to this shelter because I had been there for a while, and nobody was interested in adopting me. I am very sweet and loving and I love to be around people. I am pretty high energy, so I enjoy going out on walks, and getting lots of human interaction. I am picky with other dogs, as I am a bit of an alpha female, but the staff thinks I could do well in a home with a calm, submissive dog, preferably a male. I have a bit of a high prey drive, so the staff doesn't think I would do well with cats, but they do plan on temperament testing me with cats. So, if you have cats and are interested in adopting me, please ask staff if I have been tested with them yet, and how I did with them. I would love to find an active home with a family who will give me lots of attention and take me out for lots of walks and hikes and other outdoor activities. If you would like to meet me outside of my kennel, or if you have any questions, please ask staff.
                                                                                         Love,
                                                                                         Jilly

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Alger! I am a sweet, 2 year old, male, GSD mix. First, I would like to start off by saying I am so grateful to now be part of the AAU family. Just in time for possibly a little turkey? Unfortunately, up until now, my life has not been an easy one. I was food deprived, and as a result, extremely emaciated. I am also Heartworm positive (Stage 1) and my ears need meds too. However, the best thing about being part of the AAU family is they will provide the help and meds needed to get me well. I also will admit that I have become quite the escape artist. So, it's very important that my new family has a fenced backyard. Despite it all, I am a beautiful boy who desperately needs a family to love me. Will it be you?

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

animal.description:
(Pictured far right) We must say it would be hard to find a nicer boy then Cody. He is always happy and has never met a stranger! He is an unbelievably sweet 7 year old golden retriever who was taken to our local dog shelter by his family because they were moving. He is just an amazing boy who is good with other dogs and loves lots of attention! 

We suspect he had a bit of a hard life as he arrived at the shelter just infested with fleas. His fleas are now gone and his hair in spots is growing back nicely. He was also thin and appeared to perhaps have issues with the cruciate ligaments in both legs. Cody saw the orthopedic vet and it was confirmed he needs to have surgery on both cruciates repaired. The estimate for his first surgery is $2,476.63. 

We also found out he has a grade 5/6 heart murmur and after his ECHO was put on atenolol to make sure his heart is not working too hard. So far he is asymptomatic when it comes to the heart issue. 

He was opened up for his first surgery and unfortunately the doctor found a growth. They closed him back up and now we await the results. We will keep you posted here. We thank everyone who has donated to help this dog to date. We continue to remain hopeful and to raise money for his first surgery. Thank you so much as usual for all your help for these goldens! You'll find that donation link directly to help Cody here: 
https://www.paypal.com/donate?hosted_button_id=VRD78C79KLPBC&source=url

There will be more updates to come as we learn more about Cody. No children under the age of 10 years old with his adoption since we do not know his background.	

To adopt a Golden that you see here, please go to the Golden Retriever Rescue Resource website at www.gr-rescue.org  Read our adoption policies. If you qualify for this dogs adoption and the adoption policies, please write us for an adoption application at grrradoption@yahoo.com  Please provide your city and zip code. Please note, we only adopt to select areas within Ohio, Michigan and Indiana where we can do a home visit by a trusted volunteer. 

Please read our adoption policies on our website prior to inquiring for an adoption application. Thank you!

animal.description:
Who’s ready for a forever friend? Zeke sure is!
Zeke is a 62 lb, 1.5 year old bulldog/boxer mix with spots on his ears. 
He was rescued from Baton Rouge and brought down to New Orleans. 
Zeke wants to be friends with everybody! He is great with dogs & kids, and wants to play with every cat he meets. 
He loves to jump around, but also is very content with sleeping by your feet or on top of you (total lap dog). He is extremely intelligent and picked up learning to come, sit, and wait within a couple of days with his foster. 
He is medium energy and would do best in a home with active parents or another dog who likes to play a lot. 
Zeke is house trained. He will use his kennel, but doesn’t really like it, so he will whine for the first 5 minutes, but quickly gets used to it and sleeps throughout the night. 
He is up to date on shots, neutered and heartworm negative.

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
Bella is a 12 year old spry-spirited and loving girl. Though she's blind and a bit arthritic, her love and companionship is just like any other dog. She's still got lots of pep in her step and love in her heart and is certainly going to make a fantastic little companion. She's content with napping for parts of her day but she still enjoys going outside daily to enjoy the sun, grass, and cool breeze. She likes to be in the same room as her people but is not at all demanding. She is mobile on flat surface but cannot manage stairs or steps. Despite her vision impairment, she gets around the house quite well. She needs a quiet, adult only, home. She's good with other mild-mannered and respectful dogs and cats. She's just got such a cute little personality and is going to make someone so happy!

Fostered in Temecula, CA

If interested in ADOPTING, please fill out an adoption application online:
www.hoperanchanimalsanctuary.org/adoption-application

A copy of your application can be sent to us via email

For more information about Bella, please contact Kathy:
Call/Text: (951) 515-4077
Email: k.haley.hope.ranch@gmail.com

animal.description:
Fricka is an adult (6-7 years old )Alaskan Malamute female who loves attention, scratches and will do anything you ask of her for a treat! Fricka gets along with male dogs and would love nothing more than to have a family to call her own. Due to an eye infection prior to coming to RezQ Dogs, Fricka has limited eyesight and can really just see shadows. As a result, Fricka's ideal home would be quiet and children free. If you are interested in adding this stunning, laid back girl to your family, please contact us at adoptions.rezqdogs@gmail.com

RezQ Dogs Adoption Policies:

1. All of the dogs (and cats) adopted from RezQ Dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, de-wormed, and microchipped prior to adoption. Many of the dogs also received additional veterinary care if needed.

2. RezQ Dogs houses its dogs in private foster homes and at our facility which is open by appointment only. We do require an approved application on file prior to scheduling a meet and greet with the dog. At that point, the adopters can take the dog home.

3. Adoption fees are as follows:
 - $125 for dogs over 1 year of age
 - $150 for dogs under 1 year of age
 - $75 for cats

4. While RezQ Dogs does allow out of state adoptions, we do limit the distance between the potential adopters and our location in Dodson, MT, to within a 12-hour drive.

5. Due to our limited staff and volunteers, RezQ Dogs is unable to transport dogs to their forever homes or meet adopters part way. RezQ Dogs does not ship dogs via airlines or ground transportation. We ask the adopters to meet the dogs in person prior to adoption rather than having someone pick up the dog for them in order to ensure the right fit for both humans and dogs.

6. Please fill out our online adoption application here: www.rezqdogs.org/adopt , Make sure your application is complete and all of the phone numbers are provided as INCOMPLETE applications will not be considered. You will not be contacted if any information on the application is missing. We simply lack the manpower and time to track down the information we ask for in the first place.

7. RezQ Dogs makes every effort to reply to adoption inquiries and process applications within 1 week of receiving them. July 1, 2017, 8:18 pm

animal.description:
Zumba, a beautiful German Shepherd mix, was born in January 2018. Zumba is a sweet and gentle little girl with a sensitive soul. Zumba truly is THE PERFECT dog. Perfectly polite with great house manners, housetrained, crate trained, great with other dogs and children. Zumba loves going for walks and walks nicely on a leash, she knows basic obedience. She's smart and learns things in a heartbeat. Unfortunately, Zumba was born with a rare genetic disorder, Ehlers-Danlos syndrome. In plain English, it simply means she has very fragile skin and loose joints due to the alterations to collagen structure and density. Even the slightest scratch can damage and tear her skin requiring a trip to a veterinarian to be stitched up and time in a "cone of shame" to allow it to heal. 
We have no doubt that this fun, beautiful loving girl is worth every bit of effort but it would be so much better for her and her future if she were to have her happily ever after with someone who understands her medical needs and has the capability (financial and emotional) to deal with them. If you have the love and a nice soft lawn please dont let this sweet girl spend her life being the underdog here. As much as we love Zumba, we simply do not have the time to give her back all of the love she deserves. Any creature with this much happiness, this much love of life deserves more.
Please, if you are the reward Zumba has been waiting for, that special home, please let us know by filling out an adoption application at www.rezqdogs.org/adopt 

Adoption Policies:
1. All of the dogs (and cats) adopted from RezQ Dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, de-wormed, and microchipped prior to adoption. Many of the dogs also received additional veterinary care if needed.

4. While RezQ Dogs does allow out of state adoptions, we do limit the distance between the potential adopters and our location in Dodson, MT, to within a 12 hour drive.
5. Due to our limited staff and volunteers, RezQ Dogs is unable to transport dogs to their forever homes or meet adopters part way. RezQ Dogs does not ship dogs via airlines or ground transportation. We ask the adopters to meet the dogs in person prior to adoption rather than having someone pick up the dog for them in order to ensure the right fit for both humans and dogs.
6. Please fill out our online application at www.rezqdogs.org/adopt Make sure your application is complete and all of the phone numbers are provided as INCOMPLETE applications will not be considered. You will not be contacted if any information on the application is missing. We simply lack the manpower and time to track down the information we ask for in the first place.

animal.description:
***********************************************************
All dogs are spayed or neutered, receive a 24Petwatch microchip, collar, Luzerne County License, and their first (in a series) of shots as part of the shelter’s $120 adoption donation fee.  You are required to see your veterinarian within ten days of adoption for the state mandated RABIES VACCINE.  

Please note that this is not a complete list of the animals that we have available in the shelter. If you are actively looking for a new furry family member, please stop in often as we get new animals daily.

Please also be aware that this site is updated by volunteers and a staff member who has also volunteered to do the updates.  While some pets will have brief or even detailed descriptions, not all pets will have this. As we learn more about the pets in our care descriptions are added by those volunteers.  If a particular pet interests you, please call or visit the shelter today.  Thank you for your understanding.

Please help us make your adoption experience not only  pleasant, but quicker and easier by providing us with the following:

    * Legal ID with your current address
    * Verification of home ownership; for example a tax bill
    * A letter of permission from your landlord, along with a contact phone number.
    * Veterinary records or a letter of recommendation from your veterinarian

Macy came to us 10-29-2020 from the City of Bakersfield Animal Center.  She is the 100th dog we have rescued since the rescue began.  At 3 years old this sweet girl has been a mom way too many times but she is safe now and will never again be used for breeding. She is a lovebug for sure. She gets along with most dogs but her mama instinct kicks in and she will correct them if they are too high energy.
Note from Macy (12/23/20): My name is Macy! You want to pet me! I know you want to pet me. Just pet me!! Please please!! I love you so much. I love any attention I can get from my people. I want to show them how much I love them every time I see them. I am not shy. Some would say I am a confident dog. With the right motivation, A.K.A if you have my favorite treat you can get me to do things  like climb or jump but I am a bit of bull dozer and clumsy but I will try my best to perform. I do like to play hard but enjoy a nice leisure walk.

animal.description:
Many of us have dated "that guy/that girl at some point in our lives. You know the one - stage 5 clinger, sends 32 texts in a row if you don't respond within seconds, checks up on you at work... And while that behavior isn't exactly considered healthy in a romantic partnership, in a canine relationship, we 10/10 would recommend. 

Dorian, who is about 3 years old, is totally THAT GUY. If you're sitting, he's in your lap (all 50lbs of him). If you're walking to another room, he'll pop out of nowhere to escort you. Bathroom break? Never do it alone with Dorian! We're not trying to insinuate he's stalker-ish, but we are saying you'll never be lonely with Dorian around. 

Ok, he's a stalker. But at least he's cute! Who wouldn't want to wake up to that cute face every morning?! (Dorian also wants us to tell you he's housebroken!)

If you're interested in meeting Dorian, please visit our website to learn about our adoption process and to fill out an application, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt

All of our dogs and cats will be micro-chipped, spayed or neutered, and up-to-date on vaccinations at the time of adoption. For more photos of Dorian, follow us on Facebook Gateway Pet Guardians and Instagram @gatewaypets ... #gpgDorian. 

To view other adoptable pets from our shelter, please visit, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt

Gateway Pet Guardians is proud to offer a variety of mixed breed dogs available for adoption. However, please keep in mind that we rarely know the genetic background of the animals we rescue and, as such, we cannot guarantee the exact breed combinations found within this dog. However, we do not know his/her actual genetic makeup. Just know that this dog is probably a variety of several different breeds that have combined to create one very amazing and unique animal.

animal.description:
MEET PINKY!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession.

Here are the notes from Pinky's foster:

Pinky is my name and awesomeness is my game. When you hear the word pinky, the first things that come to mind are cute and precious and fun. I am definitely all of that and I need a home that will love me forever. When you first meet me, you will see that mas a little rough and I didn't know what it was like to have a warm bed and food and a kind hand. But thanks to being rescued by the shelter team, I am getting to have the basics every dog should have....and so much more. I will greet you with a tail wag and want you to pet me and try to sit in your lap. I am super smart and know commands and learn a new one every day. I have great leash manners and only pull if I see a four-legged friend I want to meet. But I haven't had good dog socialization yet so it's best to redirect me which is easy with treats. My sense of trying new things and liking them is incredible. Puppichino....omg, I love one every day and I am such a dainty eater. Swimming pool float....gotta take a nap on one. Car ride....head out the window time!

I would love a quiet home as the only dog where I could go for walks, hang in the yard and take a sunbath when it is cool. I need help to put on some weight that I need and someone to snuggle with. What is not to LOVE?? Email us at foster@maricopa.gov to meet this amazing dog!

This amazing pup is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4499575.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
PHOTOS:  Virtually all of our dogs have online PHOTO ALBUMS through SmugMug with LOTS of additional pictures.  Just copy and paste the link below into your browser (or simply type it in) and then search for the dog's "gallery" by name

          http://adoptasleddog.smugmug.com

VIDEOS:  In addition to photo albums, almost every dog has a video which will give you a much better "feel" for his or her personality.  NOTE:  In the new Petfinder format, it has become quite a bit more difficult to find and to play videos.  Please PAGE THROUGH the photos, looking for a photo overlaid in the center with a "play" arrow inside a circle.  This icon is white, so it can be difficult to see. 
 In many (most) cases, the video is the last photo displayed as you page through.  Just click on that photo and it will play.  Please make sure you CHECK ON THE PETFINDER VIDEO ICON, above, to see a video of this wonderful dog!  Our videos will include, at a minimum, whatever info we had on the dog upon (or shortly after) his/her arrival into our program.  There will sometimes be video updates as well.  And in every case, our Adoptions Coordinator can be emailed at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to answer questions and provide the most current information we have on the dog.  

NOTES:  Please see video or contact our Adoptions Coordinator at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM.

ADOPTION DONATION:  $250  Before adoption, all Northern Lights dogs (regardless of whether Petfinder's symbols appear) are spayed or neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and tested/treated for known parasites.
 
WHAT TO DO IF YOU WANT TO ADOPT THIS DOG:  Email us at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to request an application and get started.  WE DO NOT HAVE AN ONLINE APPLICATION - you will have to request one via email.  We will review your application to determine if there is a good fit between you and/or your family and this dog.  We may suggest another dog or dog(s) if we can offer a better fit in terms of lifestyle, experience, other pets, etc.  A vet check, reference checks, and a home visit will be conducted before an adoption can be considered for approval.  
 
NORTHERN LIGHTS DOES NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL SHELTER.  We are a nonprofit rescue organization comprised of individuals who open their private homes to foster dogs in need of a second chance..  When fosters are not available, we often pay to board a dog until space is available.  New fosters and donations to pay for boarding are always desperately needed us.  Email us at KATYLIED2@AOL.COM if you are interested in donating or for information on fostering.
 
FAQ:  For information regarding our organization, as well as adoption policies and practices, please visit our Petfinder Home Page at WWW.NORTHERNLIGHTS.PETFINDER.COM.
 
 
NOTICE:  In the vast majority of cases, the dogs in our program and rescued from shelters, and Northern Lights has no means by which to collect or verify a dog's history.  We work in concert with our veterinarians, and breed and age estimates are based on a combination of professional input and our collective experience.  Our policy with information acquired prior to acceptance and while the dogs are in our care is that of "full disclosure".  It is our goal to ensure the adopter has all available information to ensure the best possible match between the dog and the adopter(s).  If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.

Diesel has an ongoing medical condition. He was diagnosed with a disc disease causing paralysis of his two rear legs, but that hasn't affected Diesel's positive attitude. He may do well with a wheelchair. Dogs are so resilient, and Diesel still has so much love to give and get that he deserves a chance.

Diesel is the most loyal and loving dog you will find. If you have the time and the means to care for this lovebug, set up a time to meet Diesel.

animal.description: HI, my name is Selena, and I am hearing impaired (100% deaf). I am special needs so I really must have a home without young children, since I can't hear them and they can startle me. I have a ton of energy, so I will make a great walking or jogging companion. I really dislike cats and I absolutely cannot be in a home with any feline friends. I can be dog friendly but I always need a proper introduction to new dogs so that I can get to know them with my other senses. I'm really not a fan of dog parks, probably because again, I cannot hear dogs coming and they can scare me easily. Additionally, because I cannot hear what's going on around me, I tend to be a little bit more protective over my space and my humans. I am house broken and am very good at letting you know that I need to go outside. I ask for a little bit of patience when introducing me to new surroundings, but I am a quick learner and as long as you take the time to settle me in properly, I will do just fine. We could both benefit with hand signal training to work on knowing my commands. People at the ranch say that I am really sweet. I also love to chase lights for fun, devour my food, and would love to be your new best friend!

animal.description:
MEET WATSON!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. For more information, please email: amy.farner@gmail.com.

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show. We have been told that you can go straight to the shelter and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog. From what we understand, the shelter will squeeze you in. (Please know this is not a guarantee).

If you have any questions about adopting a new dog into your home or have any issues that may arise in those first few days, weeks or months, please e-mail our adoption associate, amy.farner@gmail.com and she will help you through the process. We hope your adoption process is smooth and full of happiness!

Watson is a very shy guy that is slowly adjusting to shelter life. Watson was brought to the shelter by a good samaritan who found him in the neighborhood and found him to be very hungry and thirsty. He's had a rough start to his young life. The kennel staff is working with Watson on his leash skills and he's getting better. He likes to go out to the play yard and even enjoyed playing with a friendly, female dog. He's even been doing "zoomies" around the yard and will come up to the kennel staff to get some pets and treats. However, Watson is startled easily by sudden movements or when people walk by that he doesn't know.

Watson needs a patient adopter that understands he is scared of sudden movements and will need to give him the time and patience to adapt to a new home. Watson should not go to a home with small children. Older, considerate kids would be okay. If you think Watson would be a good fit in your home, please come and meet him today!

This amazing pup is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4493710.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. animal.description:
Looks like: Piebald Dachshund Mix
Female, 10 years old, 18 pounds

Peanuts is a shy girl at first but once she feels safe, she blossoms and becomes sweet with the people around her. She really is a love and feeds off positive attention. She gets along with other dog friends and accepts getting pets from new people, but is overall wary of new situations. She is currently overweight and needs help from her person to regulate her food and get her out for walks to shed some pounds. She is good on leash and a nice little walking companion but her timidness may strike in certain situations and she could be cowering, hiding behind her person, and refusing to go. She needs help gaining confidence. 

Peanuts will benefit from have a secure yard and even more so if she has constant access to it. She is a delight and will dance for food, attention, and her way into your heart. She is great with cats, being able to live and share space with them or ignoring them all together on walks. 

Peanuts does have Pituitary Cushing's and needs to be on medication for the rest of her life to keep her hormones balanced. 

Peanuts came to us after her guardian moved into the hospital for an undetermined amount of time and could no longer care for her.

animal.description:
Please take the time to fully read Buddy’s bio before applying. If you feel Buddy is a good fit, please fill out the online adoption application found at www.collierescuenetwork.com. Please read our adoption process found at the same website before applying.  There is a $400 adoption fee for all dogs adopted through Collie Rescue Network.  

Name:  Buddy
Age:  2-3 years
Gender: Male 
Dogs: No (no dogs in the home, no dogs visiting)
Cats: Yes, dog-savvy cats are fine (he sometimes like to play chase)
Kids: age 16+ only
Medical: Season allergies (requires medication 1-2 months in late fall, approx. $75/month for 2 months)

Our boy Buddy needs a very special home.  He needs someone who is dedicated to him and love him even with his quirks (because he will, guaranteed, love you despite yours!). Once Buddy settle in and knows he is home, he is just the sweetest boy. He is very affectionate and loves nothing more than being with his humans. Hanging out with you as you putter around the house, helping you keep the squirrels away from the porch, snuggling on the couch at night to catch up on your favourite TV shows.

Buddy is not a fan of other dogs at all.  A dog free home is necessary for him to continue to be a happy boy. He will not be a candidate for dog parks or doggie visitors. But being the only dog in the home is a great way to bond with him and make it All About Buddy, which really, is what he deserves. He is fine with dog savvy cats who will understand that Buddy does, occasionally, think it’s great fun to play chase.

Buddy will do best in a more rural area that is fairly quiet. He can get overly-excited by cars, trucks, too many people, and so on. In his current foster home, in a quiet area he is doing really well and is nice and calm. Due to his reactivity in busy areas, Buddy has a bite history – he’s done loads of work now with a great behaviourist and has come a long way!  He is ready to start his search for that perfect furever family.  He needs a family who is understanding about his past, who is willing to continue to work with the behaviourist (the rescue will pay for 4 sessions, which should be more than enough), and who understands that this truly lovely little boy just wants to be someone’s Best Buddy.

Please take the time to fully read Buddy’s bio before applying. If you feel Buddy is a good fit, please fill out the online adoption application found at www.collierescuenetwork.com. Please read our adoption process found at the same website before applying.  There is a $400 adoption fee for all dogs adopted through Collie Rescue Network.

Max is a handsome, young guy looking for the Pyrfect home! He’s ready to impress you by showing off all his commands. He’s also housetrained, crate trained, and leash trained! Max’s Pyrfect home consists of an active family that will take him on nice long walks. Max needs a secure 6 ft fence as he takes his guarding duties very seriously and will easily clear a smaller fence to protect his humans from the dangerous squirrels :) Max seems to bark a bit less than a normal Pyr without sacrificing one bit of Pyr handsomeness with his beautiful, fluffy coat (he's possibly mixed with Golden Retriever). Max loves meeting new people but we are unsure about the little ones. A home with no other small critters would be best, since Max is easily distracted by them. He would enjoy a similar sized canine companion to show him the ropes of his new home. He can be protective of his food but otherwise has done well with dogs of similar size. He will happily relax in the corner of the room while you work and then eagerly jump in the car when it’s time for an adventure! Max is a very affectionate boy, looking for the right family to love. If that sounds like your family, apply for Max today!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. animal.description:
For my Petfinder,com friends, please contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information. My ID number is 335183

I am available for adoption; however due to my breed my adoption will have to be facilitated through a rescue organization. Please see the front desk staff or contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information.

Meet Sheba! Sweet girl Sheba is looking for a low-key, mellow home to call her own. Sheba came to the Shelter when her people no longer had time for her, poor girl, doesn't quite understand this or her change in living situation. Sheba walks well on a leash and knows some basic commands. At times, Sheba can be a bit shy, but once she warms, she's excited to meet you. Cuddling and being with her people are things this pretty girl really likes. Like all pets, Sheba deserves to be in loving, safe and secure home!

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption. 

Sheba did test positive for heart worm disease and is currently in treatment. She is on restricted activity for the duration of her treatment. It is very important to have your pets on heart worm preventative; this simple preventative measure will ensure that you and your pet avoid a very unpleasant and costly experience.

 Primary Color: Brown Secondary Color: White Weight: 69lbs Age: 4yrs 2mths 3wks Animal has been Spayed

animal.description:
Nope, not a real baby seal, but I do look sort of like one!

My name is Baby Seal, and I am a medium size female pittie mix who is hoping to meet my loving furever family. I weigh about 44 pounds, I am already spayed, and I just love all people (big and small), other dogs, the UPS delivery man, and probably burglars - that means I'm not much of a watch dog. I even ignore cats, and I hardly ever bark.

I do have a slight case of heartworms, but I am going to start that treatment soon and will be as good as new. But they good news is you can preadopt me and we can bond while I'm going through my treatment - talk to my foster mom.

I was pretty skinny when I came to Angels, but underweight but I now have a trim girlish figure. The vet said I am six years old, but I have plenty of playful energy. And now, I'm working on good house manners. I'm figuring out the whole "potty outside" thing.

I like to play with my toys and I give kisses and snuggles. Don't you want to come meet me?

Thank you for checking out my bio, please check back for an update. My life was saved recently and we are getting me safe and warm. Information will be updated as soon as I get settled in at my foster home.

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

animal.description:
Do you remember Honey Buns? Yum! They're so sweet and sticky, and you always want another one?

That's maybe why I'm named Honey BunBun - I'm all of those things but with a double BunBun. I'm so sweet, love to be with my people (stick right to you), and I always want more. I'm also looking for a home. Who wouldn't love having a Honey BunBun around?

I'm a 6-year-old, 55-pound, female Rottweiler mix who loves to be with people and loves attention - especially belly rubs. I never miss an opportunity for a belly rub. I'm already house-trained, and I'll go into a crate, but I'm still learning and will cry a little bit. I know what a leash is and enjoy walks, but I get excited and pull toward all the great scents.

My former home had lots of other dogs, and I did well, although my foster hasn't seen me around any yet. I'm pretty good with my foster mom's cat - the cat will let me know she's had enough and swipes my nose.

I do have a case of heart-worms. My former home didn't give me preventatives, but Angels will take care of the heart-worms, and soon, I'll be as good as new. In fact, if you think I'm the girl for you, you can pre-adopt me, take me through my treatment, and then have me for your very own. Ask my foster mom about it.

Thank you for checking out my bio, please check back for an update. My life was saved recently and we are getting me safe and warm. Information will be updated as soon as I get settled in at my foster home.

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

animal.description:
All Aboard! Destination: Forever Family! Dollar is so excited and looking forward to her trip to her new forever family! She's packed and ready to make her way there today! Dollar is a ten-year-old, thirty-pound hound mix who is sweet, gentle, and very affectionate. She's a super cuddle-bug, too! This Little Engine is crate trained and leash trained. She's on a medication that causes her to go potty more often, but the good news is that she's potty trained and will go potty outside or on pee-pee pads.

Despite coming from a hoarding situation, Dollar loves people and other dogs - she will wag her tail to show you how happy she is now! She will also give you kisses and offer her paw to you with affection. Dollar is being treated for those pesky heartworms, but this little caboose will be ready to get her play-on in no time at all!

You can't find a more loving and adoring companion than Dollar. Her gentle eyes tell you she's ready to love and be loved by the right forever family. She's a docile girl who's ready to leave the station and ride the train straight into your heart today!

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Bagel Baby! I am THE sweetest, 8 year old female, Pit mix you'll ever meet. I am so grateful to now be part of the AAU family. I am great with kids and other dogs and I get more excited about receiving love and affection than anything else, even meal times. That's all I want, LOVE and affection and to give my love and appreciation back. I even try to sit on my mommy's lap because I love her so much! I also could care less about cats! Just a few more facts about me (thought you might want to know) - I have had only had a few accidents in my foster family's house. My foster mommy thinks it was due to a change in diet. I sleep in my crate all night and I just adore car rides! Unfortunately, up until now, my life has not been an easy one. I was food deprived and heavily neglected. My foster family has helped me gain some weight and I just have a few more pounds to go. I do have an eye infection (cherry eye) and I am Heart Worm positive (Stage 1). According to my vet, my eye will be treated once I get through my Heart Worm treatment. I do need to tell you, despite all the bad things that have happened to me, the best thing about being part of the AAU family is they will provide the help and meds needed to get me well. So, please consider adopting me. I am an adorable, friendly and affectionate little girl, who desperately wants a family to love me. Will it be you?

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

animal.description:
Name: Valentina (I was pulled from the shelter on Valentine's day).

Before SOCA-FBC: I was found as a stray by FBCAS when I was only 6 months old with a severe demodex I couldn't open my eyes. Did I mention that I was also starving?

Age: 1.5 years old. My puppy life was not the best experience for me.

Energy Level: Depends on your mood. I can be a great adventure buddy or a great Netflix and chill under the covers buddy. I am very agile.

Favorite hobby: I am a certified seat warmer. I can keep a couch or bed warm. (Can you blame a girl for finally feeling comfortable?)

I also love going on car rides and hiking adventures. I am agile and ready to explore the world with you!

Other dogs: I get along well with calm and polite dogs who will also play with me. My foster home has a tiny Chihuahua and 3 medium sized dogs. Slow introduction is needed when meeting any new dogs.

Cats: No, thanks.

Kiddos: I love them, but older/considerate kids due to my random urges to do zoomies.

Super Powers: I am a cuddle bug! Oh, and I may or may not have the ability to snore like a full grown man!

Guilty Pleasures: Showing you my tummy for some lovin'. Yep, I got no shame to flip over for ya.

My resume includes: Being trained at The Houston Dog Ranch by The Texas Dog Father (I was a star student).

Skills: I am crate and potty trained. I know sit, stay, come and will wait for a command to leave the crate or go outside.

Ideal Family: Someone who is patient and structured who will continue my journey to trust the human kind. I need a firm leader that I can trust to protect me. I will need a slow introduction to any new humans or animals I meet. Several meets with me is best and my foster family will assist me in transitioning to my new home and will teach you all about me. I am weary of new people, but once I get attached, I attach. A companion dog is a plus, because it helps me gain confidence and trust.

An older kid is also a plus, I love to snuggle with them.

I am heartworm negative, spayed, microchipped and up to date on vaccines. My adoption fee is $200 and will include spay, vaccinations, and microchip. You can apply at www.soca-fbc.org/adoptables

to meet me

Gentle Bulldog needs Someone who understands PTSD

Miss Luna will pull at your heart strings. This soulful pup has suffered a lot in her 8 years of life. As a result she has PTSD and needs a calm mature home that understands PTSD. She has some incontinence issues which is hugely helped by medicine, she wears a diaper with no problem and loves to out and take walks and sit a sunny porch with her fosters. Apply only if you are willing to work with a very dear pup who has suffered in her life and welcomes kindness. Vet reference and virtual home visit required. We will transport.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Cleo. I'm somewhere around 4-5 years old. We aren't really sure because somehow I ended up in the woods out in the country.

A nice farmer saw me eating her trash and she decided to feed me and let me sleep on her porch. I lived on her porch for about a year. It was so nice having a porch to sleep on, but the thing is, I hate thunderstorms. And one night during a really bad one, I got so excited I accidentally scratched up the doorframe. I just really wanted to go inside where I felt safe.

Mr. Farmer didn't like that I scratched up the door frame so he told Mrs. Farmer she had to find a new home for me.

A fun family with three little kids came to my rescue. They are the best. I just love going on walks and hikes with them. They have another dog about my size named Ralph, and we have a great time chasing each other and battling for big sticks. The thing is, as much as I love little kids, I just can't seem to get used to them. I like giving them kisses, but their big energy and little hands make me feel uneasy. I would probably be OK with kids 12 yrs and older .

I sure am going to be sad leaving my new family. They have reminded me how wonderful it is to be a house dog again. I am looking for someone who will love me the rest of my years. I'm kind of an older girl who's ready to settle down. Walks are my favorite, but I need someone experienced with big dogs who can continue to leash train me.

I feel most comfortable lounging around the house when you're gone but I love to play outside too!

Do you think you could be my forever owner?

https://greatdanefriends.com/cleo

Please contact Great Dane Friends (info@greatdanefriends.com) for more information about this pet.

*****Great Dane Friends of Ruff Love covers NC and surrounding states for adoptions. We require a fenced yard (exceptions made on a case by case basis - NO exceptions for puppies or deaf/vision impaired dogs - no invisible fencing), that stairs in the home be covered with some sort of slip resistant material to prevent injury, that all other animals in the home be up to date on vaccinations as well as spayed/neutered and that all dogs live inside as a part of the family. Our approval process consists of an application, vet and reference checks, phone interview and house check. Please email us for an application or if you have any questions.*****

animal.description:
Little Sadie came to OHAR in an emergency situation - the people who found her couldn't keep her, Sadie was emaciated and couldn't walk!

One of OHARs fosters stepped up to give this little girl a soft spot to land while she was being medically evaluated. Fearing the worst, the news came in.. Sadie had a shattered pelvis. Over the next 8 weeks Sadie was an outstanding patient for her foster while on 100% crate rest. She was quiet as a church mouse but squirmed like a wiggle worm while getting belly rubs and all over scratches from her foster mom. 

Crate rest is over and Sadie has a clean bill of health on her pelvis. She can move about and play with the other dogs although she is still rebuilding the muscles of her back legs and does get a little wobbly at times. As Sadie's health continues to improve her stability and balance will continue to increase.

Sadie is house trained; she has had an occasional overnight bladder leak from her injury. With medication and time this has greatly improved. She is great with other dogs large and small and will play at the drop of a hat. If a human is near she will make a beeline to get her scratches before anything else! We don't know her history but given her state coming in it is no surprise she does a little resource guarding with food and toys. Once she begins to get comfortable with the dogs around her this dissipates to an occasional grumble. Recommend feeding separately for at least the first two weeks.

Last, as if everything else were not enough, Sadie tested heartworm positive. She is on medication in advance of her first treatment in October.

animal.description:
Meet Uni! This 2 year old, ice blue-eyed boy is the dog you need by your side! Not too long ago, his rescuer found him on the street, unresponsive and covered from head to tail in wounds and infection. His left ear was so infected that it flopped down 90 degrees!

Fast forward to today…Uni is enjoying life to the fullest, so don’t let his RBF fool you! His favorite activities are going for walks, getting chin scratches, and meeting new dog friends! Being part husky, he’ll happily let you know just how excited he is, but while you work, he’s just as happy to lay quietly at your feet and nap. He’s still learning to play with toys since he most likely has never seen one, but he’ll engage in dog puzzles (anything for treats)! Uni is house-trained, crate-trained, working on commands, and once fully recovered, will be the perfect running companion. He is heartworm positive, but has begun treatment and will soon beat those pesky worms. 

Uni’s ideal forever home will have a very secure backyard (as escape artist is in his husky genes) and would have a doggie sibling to play with. However, he has done well as solo dog in his foster’s home. He’s done well with children he’s met on walks. Uni is also potty trained and does just fine in a crate too - just no kitties please.
animal.name: Uni

animal.description:
Hi everyone, my name is Hogan. I’m a handsome 82lb, 2 year old Shepherd mix in search of my forever home.  I was found running in the streets of Houston. My foster mom who is a vet tech was on her way home from work and saw me eating garbage at a railroad track. She tried to get me but I was scared and took off running. She didn’t give up and followed me for 1/2 a mile before finally catching me. I was terrified, hungry and thirsty.  It took me awhile to warm up. People haven’t treated me well so it takes me time to trust. I’m house trained, kennel trained and sweet as can be.  I do well with some dogs and play very gently.  I would do better in a home that has older children and a calm environment. I’m learning to play ball and I walk well on a leash.  I may always be a little nervous of new things so I will require an experienced home. I’m a big love bug. 
With Love Hogan

Bigloverescue.org for an adoption application. Hogan is in a foster home and we must have an approved application of file before we make an appointment for a meeting.

animal.description:
Senior Woobie is looking for a new home to live out the rest of her golden years. Woobie’s owner passed away in August and the sister has been keeping her. Now that she is moving in with her father, the father said Woobie can’t live with them.

Woobie has always been such a blessing to our family. She brought us all together & showed us each so much love. Since she was a puppy she’s always carried such a happy personality. Woobie was born on Christmas Eve 2013. We were told she’s an American bulldog. She’s potty trained. She loves food. She loves to play fetch. She’s not too great with other dogs because she’s very territorial but we’ve been living with my moms dog for over a year now & they get along great now. Shes never been around cats. She’s always been amazing with small children & babies!! Very sweet & patient. She’s good in the car. Woobie loves to be walked but she must stay on a leash at all times!! She loves to snuggle & be pet. She’s a very low maintenance dog all she needs is love & treats of course.

She does not like being kenneled. She is a free roaming house dog. 

She is difficult sometimes to walk cause she wants to pull and go towards other dogs. Since she never played with other dogs growing up her dog skills are lacking and because of her size it would be best to have her own yard and no other pets. Otherwise, it will take time, patience and could be too risky. 

When no other dogs are around she is great on leash going on walks

Apply for Woobie at tmldogrescue.com

animal.description:
Major is a 2-3 year old Shar-Pei mix. He is quite statuesque and beyond handsome. He is a very active boy who plays hard. You must earn his trust when first meeting him. Shar-Peis are known to be very intelligent and loyal. Major would benefit from some obedience training to help him bond with his owner and give him a better sense of who is in charge. He will require a physical fence.
AHeinz57 Pet Rescue and Transport is a 501c3 no-kill animal rescue located in De Soto, Iowa. Our pets are located at our facility and in foster homes around Central Iowa. We do adopt to out of town applicants, however we do require new family members be picked up in person. 

If you are interested in meeting one of our adorable adoptables, the first step in our process is to complete an adoption application. To complete an application or read more about our adoption process, please visit our website:

https://www.aheinz57.com/adopt-a-pet/adoption-process/
Our adoption fees are:

$300 - Puppies (up to 6 months)

$195 - Dogs age 6 months - 7 years

$100 - Senior Dogs (age 8 and up)

$200 - Bonded Buddies

$100 - Kittens (up to age 6 months)

$150 - 2 Kittens

$60 - Cats age 6 months and up

$90 - 2 Cats

For the most up-to-date listing of adoptable animals, please visit our website: https://www.aheinz57.com/adopt-a-pet/

Thank you for considering adopting a rescue animal!

***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

 

Hi. I move socks.

I love EVerything about living in a house-My food...your food. My bed...your bed. My toys...your toys. 

I love people after I get used to them. I love boy dogs even faster. I don't know any girl dogs currently, but did ok with them before. I am very energetic and strong so probably wouldn't be best for tiny humans. I also get too excited and think that nipping is included in playing sometimes, so that's a work in progress.

I look all black in some pictures, but I'm really dark gold with a black racing stripe so I can run fast and play forever, but when I'm done running around I like things to chew on. I am also super silly, a level 72 certified Nap Master and belly rubs are my favorite.

Ideally I'd like a yard and another furry sibling to play with and humans that will continue my training. I'm a good girl, but still have a lot to learn.

 

I am spayed, up-to-date on vaccinations, microchipped, have been dewormed, and am current on my monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. My adoption fee is $300. If you think I could be the one for you, please fill out an application on our website: www.secondchancenc.org. Thank you!

animal.description:
Lyla is a sweet, affectionate Golden Retriever mix who was born in December of 2018. This sweetie pie is looking for a new home with no children. Lyla does love to play with other small and larger dogs BUT SHE DOES GUARD her food and toys from them so they would have to be tolerant of her sometimes sassy attitude and her owners would have to be watchful of her guarding. Due to this, it is suggested that dogs be separated when owners not at home.

Lyla enjoys her toys and doesn't really like to share. A fenced yard is a definite plus because she loves to play outside.

Lyla does some resource guarding so she would not fit in a home with children due to this personality trait. Lyla, who already knows some basic commands, is a smart girl who thrives on treats and positive reinforcement. Due to events in her past, she does not like anyone touching her neck and collar. She comes fully house trained and vetted!! Lyla may need a few minutes to warm up to new people, especially men, but she is able to adjust quickly! If you have the time and patience to help Lyla become her best self, fill out an application today!

Please note: Lyla has guarding issues and will need to be placed in a home with prior dog experience. Adopter also will be required to work with our positive reinforcement trainer so her treatment plan to address her guarding tendencies can continue in the adoptive home. Also no children in the home.

Update 1/11/20. Lyla's best friend was adopted and she really misses running and playing with another dog. A playful dog her size or larger would be ideal. Lyla is currently on a diet as she gained a couple pounds over the holiday. She has also gotten much, much better with her resource guarding. And she loves to play fetch!

The suggested adoption donation for Lyla is $350, which is TAX DEDUCTIBLE, and goes toward providing supportive services to animals in the home, as well as the high cost of vetting our dogs in rescue. If you would like to welcome Lyla into your home, please begin by submitting our Adoption Application. The adoptions for all of our dogs will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver the dogs. If you would like to learn more about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue, or donate to our dogs, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com. We invite you to visit our Facebook Page, and when you visit, please don't forget to Like our Facebook page so that you wont miss any information about our dogs and events!

animal.description:
Zoie is a spunky 10-year-old Weimaraner/Husky mix, looking for a loving home. She is timid and nervous at first around strangers, especially men. Fast movements are a little scary for her so a quiet, low traffic home with no small children would be best for her. She loves to go on walks where she can take her time sniffing all the wonderful smells along the way or to meander around the yard. And after being outside, a nice snuggle on the couch with a soft blankie is right up her alley! She has lived in an apartment and house and would do well in either setting. She is quiet, potty trained and not destructive when left alone. She has lived with a cat before however she currently does not like to share her space with other dogs. She would really appreciate a calm, patient home that can help her thrive and be the best little old lady that she can be!

Potential adopters will have access to Muddy Paws trainers to help Zoie have the smoothest transition to her new home. Adopters should expect several meetings with Zoie to get her used to them before bringing her home. 

The suggested adoption donation for Zoie is $250.00. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of
veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs
foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be
done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right
applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months. To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Name: Colton
Suspected Breed(s): Australian Cattle Dog/Bully Breed mix
Gender: Male
Age: 2 years old
Weight: 60 lbs
Personality: Smart, gentle, energetic, goofy, shy, playful, and friendly.
Observations with Dogs: Generally good with other dogs. There are two other dogs in his foster home, and after a short adjustment period he does very well with both of them.
Observations with Cats: Untested
Observations with Kids: Untested
House Training Progress: No recent accidents. 
Crate Training Progress: Colton is mostly quiet in the crate. Sometimes he whines loudly when initially left alone (e.g., foster parent/dogs go upstairs), but he is learning to settle down.
Location: DC Area Foster
Rescued From: Columbus County, NC
Additional Information: Colton is a darling dog who has lots of fun with his chew toys. This sweet boy is sometimes startled when getting pets, and he is learning the joys of living in a home with loving humans. Colton gets thrown off by loud noises while out on walks, and he would probably not do well in a dense neighborhood. With some more TLC and training, Colton is on his way to becoming a wonderful furever friend!

__________________________________

If you are interested in meeting a dog or cat, we require an adoption application. If the animal has "HAS APPLICATION" listed, they are still available to receive additional applications but also may be in the process of being adopted soon. Apply for a DOG: http://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/adoptable-dogs.html

Interested in saving more lives? Foster a dog today! Learn more, see our list of dogs needing foster, and apply, https://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/foster-a-city-dog.html

City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is a foster based rescue in Washington, DC. We do not have a shelter. We focus on local adoptions in DC and the metro area of Maryland and Virginia. CDR&CK has a thorough adoption process in order to find the best possible fit for each of our dogs and cats (we do not operate under a first-come, first served model).

Upon accepting a new cat or dog into the organization, we provide a basic vet visit that includes necessary vaccinations, disease screenings, deworming, microchips, and spay/neuter (unless specified). We do not provide a comprehensive medical exam prior to adoption. As a result, sickness, injury, and disability may exist unbeknownst to CDR&CK. City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is not responsible for payment of any vet care, including known and unknown medical conditions once a cat or dog is adopted from us. 
Dog specific: Rabies, DHPP, Bordatella vaccines. They are tested for HW, Lyme, Ehrlichia, Anaplasmosis.

Most cats and dogs will have a house training accident in the initial days in their new home and we cannot guarantee any pet is housebroken or crate trained.

We also update our Facebook page daily with new cats and dogs.

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS & PROCEDURES
Mutt Match L.A. does not adopt out of state nor do we adopt on a first come first serve basis but rather to the home that is best suited for each particular dog and breed. An application, home check, contract and adoption fee are required for all adoptions. All dogs will be, or required to be, spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations and microchipped before adoption. Most of our dogs are from local LA area shelters, we generally have no prior history for them.
Adoption fees vary between $400 - $500 for puppies 8 weeks - 5 years, $350 6 - 9 years and $300 for dogs over 9 years. Adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip a wellness check, any additional medical expenses necessary and of course the all the love and daily care we take with each dog before they are adopted.
We believe a well behaved dog is a happy dog and companion. Therefore, we require at least one session with one of our recommended behaviorists for a reduced fee which is not included in the adoption fee.
We are a busy fully functioning rescue and facility, unfortunately, we do not take requests for more photos and/or video. The photos you currently see are what we currently have and are updated as we recevie new photos. For additional information or questions, please email us at info@muttmatchla.org. To submit an application, please visit us at www.muttmatchla.org. Mutt Match L.A. is an all volunteer rescue, please allow at least 48 hours for a returned response of all inquires.
Thank you! We look forward to hearing from you soon.

Anyone missing their quiet furry shadow? We’ve got a scruffy Huckleberry waiting to be by your side! This handsome black and tan pup is 5 years old and the perfect 30 lb size. He had a rough start to his young life but has really blossomed in foster care, and now he’s ready for a family of his own!

Huck arrived at the shelter in severely neglected condition at the beginning of this covid debacle. He was quickly adopted, and returned – twice – by families that just weren’t a good fit. Thankfully we had a foster home available by then, and when the shelter reached out to ask for help finding his perfect match next time around, we were happy to say yes. We’ve had a chance to see this sweet boy gain confidence and really come out of his shell. And you know what? The dog beneath that soft wavy fur is a true gem who’s ready to shine his way into your heart.

Huckleberry boy is looking for a quiet adult home with low foot traffic, and hopefully a private yard of his own. Loud noises can startle him and a bustling area is not his style. He’s a chill dude, after all! He enjoys a couple nice walks each day and is content to lay quietly at your feet while you’re working. Crate trained and house broken, our lil diamond is also not a barker. He’s shy around new people at first but warms up with patience and time, and once you’ve earned his trust, he’s a most affectionate chap who enjoys belly rubs and scratches. Huck could live with a well-matched doggie pal but he’d also be fine flying solo with folks who are home a lot. He hasn’t met any cats on our watch but we think he’d probably be ok with a savvy feline too.

Where’s the lucky family who will adopt our gentle lowrider? If he sounds like the soulmate you’ve been searching for, reach out today and ask about Huckleberry boy!

Southern California adopters only please!

Facebook: https://facebook.com/waggingdogrescue/photos_albums

Adoption Application: 
https://waggingdog.org/adopt/

Website: https://waggingdog.org
Email: adoptions@waggingdog.org
