animal.description:
Hi, I'm Hank, a beautiful cream and black appx 3 yr old German Shepherd mix.  I'm a very sweet, happy, feisty pup!   I love to run and jump and play with my foster daddy and my best Husky buddy Bandit!  Bandit probably just got adopted, though, so I'm REALLY LONELY without him!!  :(

From my foster daddy: Hank is a playful, happy dog!  He tends to jump on me when he first sees me bc he's so happy to see me, but once he calms down, he wants to be my shadow and shows OVERWHELMING LOVE!! :)  He likes to lay down near me, sometimes with his head on my foot!  :)  :)

He gets along well with people, other dogs and kids (we have a 2 yo granddaughter who he gently tries to get close to). He has a very playful temperament.  He loves to wrestle with his male Husky buddy, Bandit. They play all day long & he has NO aggression towards dogs or other people. 

He's a bit shy at first, but then he falls in love.  He's very good walking on a leash. I walk him on the left side w a choker chain & correct him w slight tugs on the leash. He barks a little in the yard at other dogs / squirrels that go by, but is not bad about it. 

I recommend @ least a 6' fence and/or invisible fence and a decent sized yard.  He would jump or run off if the fence is too low or the gate is left open.

Hank may need some work on potty training bc he's had to spend a lot of time outside. He's not cat-tested and we haven't tried crate training.

We feed him Purina One -- Lamb & Rice -- with a dash of DINOVITE supplements, twice/day,  1-1/2 cups/feeding.  *As with ALL DOGS, Hank is best  fed separately from other dogs to avoid any food competition.*

WILL YOU GIVE SWEET HANK A LOVING HOME AND FAMILY TO CHERISH??

animal.description:
Meet this happy girl named Nina! She came into the shelter early November 2020 when her owner could no longer keep her and there was no one else to care for her. She is 1 year old, current on shots, and just a happy girl. She can be shy around people she doesn’t know but once she warms up and knows you you will have a FOREVER friend in her. She loves to run and play fetch with a toy, ball, or stuffed animal. Just a beautiful girl inside and out. Might you have the most amazing loving FOREVER home for sweet Nina?! Stop by the shelter for a visit with her and give her back the awesome life she’s missing! A FOREVER home! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

Scooter was quite isolated her first few years, then banned from the house, when she was 'rescued' by a family member who knew what a loving dog she IS & she loves belly rubs & cuddles ! If you have dogs she would love that. She loves to play. Give her time/tenderness ~she will become your best friend with her tail wagging always ! Her difficulties are food aggression (must be fed separately) , door darting (would need fenced yard) A couple or single person or family w/ older children (we have found, due to not ever being around them, she is uncertain of children's quick moves). }  4-5 yr old, 52 lb, house trained. She was afraid around new people, groups, but has done so well at events.  She is heartworm positive & has had 30 days doxycycline & taking the 6 applications of Advantage Multi-Important NEW information on this treatment kills the worms & dogs are testing negative 3 (smaller dogs) to 6 months. We had “before” & “after” ECHO on a 50 lb dog & worms were dead & safely being absorbed in the body!!  She has NO symptoms of health issues !!!
***
Thank you for your interest in applying to adopt ! Events slowly being scheduled due to pandemic.....watch LOVE Mutts Rescue Facebook for all calendar events, & info. Meet by appointment w/ approved application.  Website, has current available pets, links to donation (we are non-profit) & to adopt & volunteer www.lovemuttsrescue.org  We will email you our process & fees. animal.description:
Chandler
Dachshund blend, 12 lbs., 2-3 years old 

Hi, my name is Chandler! I am about 2-3 years old and I weigh about 12 lbs. The humans around me say they think I am a Dachshund/Terrier blend of some sort. I'm not really sure what that means but I understand them when they say how beautiful I am ?.

I really am a good boy and I want to make the humans around me happy, but I'm really SCARED of just about EVERYTHING. I am easily startled over everyday noises that other pooches wouldn't be. Things like setting a glass on the table or putting your fork down on your plate, for instance, put me on edge. The list of things that startle me is endless ?. I will even run outside, through the dog door, sometimes when my humans enter the room, especially if they're wearing boots. This also means that fast movements and excited kiddos are a big NO in my world. I just don’t have the ability to adjust to little people, it’s super scary to be around them. 

Don't get me wrong, there have been a few times when I have let my foster people pet me, and I enjoyed it. What I really need is someone super special that is willing to give me all the time in the world that I need to become comfortable. I'm not sure if that means 3 months or maybe even 3 years. Heck, I may never become totally comfortable but I'm sure there is that special someone out there that is looking just for me.

I am potty trained in my current foster home, with a doggie door, so having a doggie door and a secure fenced backyard really is a must for me. I really enjoy the company of the other dogs in my foster home, and I will need a canine companion in my new home to show me the ropes, and help me become more comfortable.

Fostered in Eugene/Springfield, Oregon

Adoption fees help cover the costs of Transport, Distemper/Parvo Boosters, Rabies shot, Microchip, and Spay/Neuters, as well the dog comes with a collar, harness and leash. You will also receive a PetSmart puppy packet with 100.00's of dollars of savings, you get a FREE bag of food, 30 min private training session with a certified dog trainer as well as a free checkup at Bandfield. Adoption fee is $350.00.

Please E-mail wigglytailsdogrescue@yahoo.com if you would like an application. Just because you request an application in no way guarantees you a dog as we receive several applications and will choose the best home for the dog.

Must live within 30 Miles of Eugene!! If you live outside the 30 area still send an email as some time we can make special arrangements. 

Wiggly Tails Dog Rescue is proud to rescue dogs in urgent need and to also assist local owners who can no longer care for their small breed dog. All our dogs are up to date on their shots and spay or neutered.  We do require a foster or adoption application for those interested and will visit your home for a meet and greet before releasing the dog to you.

You can check out our other adoptable dogs at: www.wigglytails.org or http://www.facebook.com/WigglyTailsDogRescue. We are located in Eugene, Or and require a home check so interested adopters need to be local.

He came in about 5-10lbs underweight but doing well now that he is in foster care. He is very sweet, affectionate, great with other dogs and likes to play with tennis balls. His cage training and house training is going well- but he does need some work on his manners- like counter surfing. Oliver is sadly positive for heartworms, but we have a great program that is easier on the dogs without any exercise restrictions. Pointers are the best dogs and for their safety we do require safe fenced in yards.

I would like to line up a foster to adopt home for Oliver in the Chicago area that can help with his care. If you would like to help, please copy and paste the link into your browser to view: http://illinoisbirddogrescue.org/foster_app.html and submit a foster to adopt home application. You can also call Lisa@ 630-694-1359

animal.description:
CRUZ ?
Chihuahua blend, 12 lbs., 5 years old

Sweet, little Cruz is a darling girl. She is slow to open up to new people and surroundings, though she will let you know she loves you when she settles down next to your feet. ??

Our girl is seeking a loving and patient home, that will offer her the time she needs to feel comfortable. If you are hoping for an “in your face”, super outgoing pup, she does not have that personality trait. What she does have is a gentle nature that will offer her forever person or family her loyal friendship for all of her days. 

Cruz is potty training and has been successful using a doggie door, which shows is just how easy she is to adapt to new ways of doing things. 

To further inquire about Cruz, send us a PRIVATE MESSAGE with your email address and phone number. Tell us about yourself, family, other pets, and how she will mesh with your lifestyle. 

Qualifying applicants will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator with next steps and an opportunity to set up a Meet & Greet. 

Our process is not a “first come, first served” process. Our team carefully reviews and interviews applicants for the best possible fit for each adoptable dog, and potential family.  We look forward to facilitating a positive and solid adoption for Cruz, as well as her future family. ?
*Fostered in Eugene/Springfield, Oregon

Adoption fees help cover the costs of Transport, Distemper/Parvo Boosters, Rabies shot, Microchip, and Spay/Neuters, as well the dog comes with a collar, harness and leash. You will also receive a PetSmart puppy packet with 100.00's of dollars of savings, you get a FREE bag of food, 30 min private training session with a certified dog trainer as well as a free checkup at Bandfield. Adoption fee is $300.00.

Please E-mail wigglytailsdogrescue@yahoo.com if you would like an application. Just because you request an application in no way guarantees you a dog as we receive several applications and will choose the best home for the dog.

Must live within 30 Miles of Eugene!! If you live outside the 30 area still send an email as some time we can make special arrangements. 

Wiggly Tails Dog Rescue is proud to rescue dogs in urgent need and to also assist local owners who can no longer care for their small breed dog. All our dogs are up to date on their shots and spay or neutered.  We do require a foster or adoption application for those interested and will visit your home for a meet and greet before releasing the dog to you.

You can check out our other adoptable dogs at: www.wigglytails.org or http://www.facebook.com/WigglyTailsDogRescue. We are located in Eugene, Or and require a home check so interested adopters need to be local.

FOSTER HOME URGENTLY NEEDED. Malkin is currently located in the Charlotte area. If you have room in your heart and home to give a hound a second chance, please fill out an ONLINE FOSTER HOME APPLICATION

This good looking 8 year old gentleman is looking for a family to call his own. While we do not know much about where Malkin spent most of his life, we think he worked hard and spent time with other dogs. He would thrive in a multiple dog home; he likes being outside with the pack. Exercise is key to his happiness, as it helps him settle into the day. Structure is also important to him and he does best with a predictable schedule. He has a great voice and likes to use it, so his new home should be prepared for classic hound song notifications throughout the day. A house on a busy street probably would not be ideal. He would also do best in a home with older adults and no small children. Malkin weighs about 90 pounds and is currently hanging out with his foster mom's pack north of Charlotte.

animal.description:
Sterling is an older dober boy around 8 who was recently surrendered back to the rescue due to life changes in his forever foster's life.

A little back story on sweet Sterling: rescued along with his pregnant lady friend in 2018; they had lived their lives outside in runs with very little to no human interaction. Sadly all of the puppies passed away, and his lady friend has since been adopted. Sterling can be very shy at times but once he warms up to you, he loves you with everything he has. He has a very endearing trot, we believe he was hit by a car at one point.

Sterling tippy taps with his front paws when he gets excited. We really, really would love to see him in a home again, a nice calm environment either as an only pet or with a female dog. This amazing dober has been through a lot, and now it's finally time for him to get a home of his own. Forever.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Hallow! I was rescued by a great samaritan who found me hiding under a trailer in the Redlands. She brought me and my 8 puppies to the Big Dog Ranch to get some love and care. I am very sweet but I need to get to know you before I'm willing to let you play with my babies. I love to have all of your attention and get as much love from you as possible. While I haven't been tested with other dogs or cats, it seems that I may be able to live in a home with other animals, if they're the right ones! It would probably be best for me to find a home with an experienced dog owner who can help me learn how to be a more homebody, since I spent so much of my life living outside. I think I could be very happy living in a variety of different environments, from apartments to a big house with lots of land, as long as I have a new family that gives me all of their love. I think that I would like to be the type of dog that joins you as you go out and about and I appear to be potty trained already! I would benefit from some continued training so that I can be the absolute best pup that I can be. I love to go for long walks on the leash, I think I could be an excellent running buddy, but my absolute favorite thing to do would be to lay around and snuggle on the couch with you!

animal.description:
Meet Pancake!

Pancake is a six year old little spitfire. She arrived from Best Friends Atlanta in 2017. She is very enthusiastic about life, loves to play and play bite, and would do best in a home with adults only. Pancake does and has lived with dogs here at the Sanctuary and has decent dog skills. She does guard resources from dogs and humans, so some level of management would have to occur in the home. 

Pancake enjoys walks with her run mate Ron Swanson. She loves to go on car rides, to Tara's Run, and the dog park as well.

Pancake did pass her first cat test! So she may be able to live with feline friends. 

Pancake does require relationship building before she is able to go home. This process does take two to three weeks. A Sanctuary visit is required. Once you are her friend, you are a friend for life! She is so much fun and always down for adventure.

If you are willing to put in the time for this fiery girl, reach out to our adoption team and fill out an application today!

animal.description:
Meet Goose—a handsome and lovable Pitbull mix with a touch of German Shepherd (my dad was half German Shepherd believe it or not).  I am 9 months old, neutered, 70lbs and very loved.  I am house trained and kennel trained but I  probably wouldn’t leave me in the house unattended just yet - I’m still learning to be trustworthy. .  I am calm and chill by nature but have the occasional spurt of puppy energy and need to zoom around a yard for a bit.  I am wonderful with kids.  I love long walks with my people, romping outside or lying at your feet after a long day.  I am well behaved naturally but like most dogs could probably use a little formal training.  I love to give kisses and give them unabashedly if allowed. I know, I sound pretty perfect and I am, so why do I need another family to love me?  Unfortunately, I no longer get along with the other 2 dogs in the house.  This doesn’t make me a bad dog, just a dog that needs to be the one and only.  I can walk by dogs on leash and behave in public.   I just don’t like to share my space anymore. I would be the most wonderful and devoted companion and friend to another family but I really need to be the only pet in the house.  What can I say - I need all of the attention and will give you all of mine. 

PACA is a foster based rescue with no shelter to view our dogs.  We have temporarily stopped all our public adoption events due to COVID-19, however we are still placing dog into loving homes by private appointment with approved applications.  

Completed applications will be given to the foster to coordinate meetings as everyone feels comfortable.  This application helps us get to know you and your family a little better so we can find the perfect match! Application are found here:
http://nmpaca.org/images/pdf_files/PACA_Adoption_Application.pdf
Please email completed applications to pacadogs@aol.com 

All our animals are spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for tic born illness and heartworm prior to adoption.  Our fee is $175.
animal.name: Goose

animal.description: Spicy! This is how one of our volunteers described Chico, and we couldn't agree more. He IS spicy, and we love that about him! Chico is also very affectionate and gives the sweetest little kisses. He really is that perfect combo of sweet and spicy! Chico is a smart pup - he knows sit, down, and shake. Chico picks up on new things quickly, and he is so eager to please his person. Chico is one of those pups who loves everyone he meets, and it's simply impossible not to love him back! Chico has been in foster for several months and we have learned so much about him. Chico will nap most of the day, but he will occasionally check in with you to make sure you haven't forgotten him! Chico gets that burst of energy in the evenings that we call the witching hour - it's important that you exercise his brain as much as his body during this time. Puzzle toys, kongs, marrow bones... make sure you are stocked up! When it's time for bed, scooch over and make room for Chico! He loves to sleep in bed with his person but he is very polite and will not invade your space. He's happy to let you sleep in but then he needs some yard time or a long walk in the morning to get his day started on the right foot. Chico is house trained and is making great progress on his crate training. He doesn't love his crate but he will go in for the right treat. Chico will sleep in it on his own during the day... he loves to curl up in the soft blankets! An ideal home for Chico would be one where he gets to go on a few walks/runs each day, or one that has a yard for him to run around in (or both!). Chico is quite dog reactive so he would need to be the only pet. He also needs an adult-only home. If you have experience with cattle dogs, and know about their needs and behaviors, you could be a great fit for Chico! We won't sugarcoat it... Chico can be a lot of dog. But we know his perfect family is out there, and he is so deserving of a forever home! Chico will go home with a crate, goody bag, harness, free training voucher, and the ongoing support of his volunteer advocates, the Orange Dot Crew. Please email his foster for more information: dloignon@gmail.com

animal.description: Foster Boomer came to us all the way from Alabama. He was found on the streets and for weeks no-one came forward for him. This sweetheart is around 8 years old, missing one eye and severely vision impaired in the remaining eye. That doesn't seem to have slowed him down. He takes walkabouts around the house and is learning the lay of the land. In just 2 days he knows where the water bowl, food bowl and back door are. He is learning his way back to his crate when it is time for a rest from his adventures. He does very well in his crate and sleeps in it through the night. He gets excited when he hears dinner being prepared and gives a few barks to let you know he knows something good is coming his way. He seems to be house broken. He gets along well with my other dog and is not bothered by the cat. He spent the day with the grand daughters loving on him and he is great on a leash!! He seems to have some hearing loss, although he can hear the dinner bell!! Unfortunately, Boomer came to us with every worm imaginable - tapeworms, hookworms and of course heartworms so he will be with us for a while until his treatments are completed. Put your application in for this sweet boy, he is worth the wait.

animal.description:
Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Phoenix

Dog's Approximate Age: 1.5 -2 years

Gender: Male

Dog's Size: Medium (50lbs to 70lbs. as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 52 pounds

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Don't know yet

Good with kids?: Yes, all ages

Any medical issues?:

Crate trained?: Yes

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: No

12/17/20: HELLO!! Its Phoenix from Sanford. I've come a LONG way the month and a couple days since I been in my foster home. My BIGGEST issue was my weight. I started my life with my foster family at 29 pounds. Foster Daddy has been feeding me every chance he gets. The first week I was eating 4 times a day and eating snacks 3 times a day. The second week up until my neuter (yesterday) I have been eating 3 times a day and snacks 2-3 times a day. He is trying to get me to a solid 60 pounds and I don't have far to go. My foster house is great, I have 3 sisters. Izzy and Lucy are bigger than me and my older sister Bella is way smaller than me. They loved me from the first time I came into their home. They wash my face, and sleep close to me to keep me warm. My first 2 weeks I wore this awesome sweater all day to keep me warm. They were gentle with me when I was weak and tiny, now that I have become a big boy they run and play with me in the backyard. Foster Daddy says I'm such a smart boy, I'm silly at times especially when my belly is full of warm nummy's. I love to snuggle at bed time with my sisters or my Daddy. I do great in the kennel during the day while everyone is at work. Daddy sometime lets me stay out with my sisters when he is not gone for a long time, NO ACCIDENTS FOR ME!!!! Today Daddy took me to work and I got all kinds of belly rubs and back scratches. Naomi (16) took me for a walk at work and I was AWESOME. She was not afraid of me, and I was not afraid of her. I will say Naomi did have a pocket FULL of treats. I have some boys that come over to see me and Daddy, they are 3, 10 and 12. I love them, I wish they lived with me cause I'd sleep with them. I've been on field trips to the hardware store, the feed store and the pet store. Its nice to get out of the back yard and do fun things with Daddy. Daddy says I was very smart in all the stores and I always get kisses on my head for being a good boy. I love warm food that fills my belly also frozen uncooked beef bones are the best. Daddy says I will a great dog for any family soon. Daddy is working with me on the leash and my smart boy commands. I'm almost there!

11/15/20: Hi!! I'm PHOENIX, that's my new name. I'm new to CBR by way of Virginia. Dad gave me a new name, said my old name was not strong enough. One day I'll be that strong but right now I don't feel good and like my dad said "I seen more meat on a cheese sandwich". Dad picked me up on Veterans Day and I was not doing well so we had to stop at the Vet before I could go home. I do love to eat, dad feeds me 3 times a day!!!. I'll be BIG and STRONG soon, daddy says I already have the handsome part down (WINK). I have 3 sisters and they wash my face, boo boo's and snuggle with me to keep me warm at night. My new life is awesome. Anyway, watch me grow. Daddy says I'll rise from the old ashes of Cody and transform to a PHOENIX. Check me out later.

_____________________________________________________________________________

Come visit carolinaboxerrescue.org to learn more about me and see more pictures. Learn about our adoption process too!

_____________________________________________________________________________

animal.breeds_label: Staffordshire Bull Terrier & German Shepherd Dog Mix
animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.DNA results are inAren't I gorgeous! The rescue thinks I am something special. So special in fact, that they took me in, paid for my surgeries and then sent me off to a trainer for some basic skills. What a catch I am.
My name is Crash - I was hit by a car and taken to Eastex Veterinary in Humble, Tx. I had 2 broken legs. It was painful, and I needed to be crated for a long time to heal. But, I am better now and ready for my forever home.
I am great with people, and kids, although I am a bit clumsy, I would prefer kids that are a bit older and won't be knocked down by my wiggle butt. I am a great big lover and will give you lots of kisses and love. My foster mom did a DNA test on me and the results were surprising.
62.5% American Staffordshire Terrier12.5% German Shepherd Dog
12.5% Chow Chow
12.5% Guard/Sporting/Terrier.
This includes a Great Dane which would account for my height.
I am a puppy and will need to have a loving patient family who is dedicated to my future, which means I may need professional training.
I would love to meet you to see if we are a good fit. =========================================================
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
BONDED WITH SISTER-MUST BE ADOPTED TOGETHER

Looking for a forever foster family or an adopted family. What does it mean to be a forever foster? That means that we pay the medical bills. 

Lily is 12 years old brindle chiweenie. Very sweet dog, just wants to be by your side. She gets anxious at first in new situations and hates fireworks. She is a nest builder, if you give her a couple blankets she builds an intricate nest, it is fun to watch. Probably not dog friendly besides grace who she's been with for 10 years. 

Grace is 12 years old chihuahua. She is fun and playful, loves toys, just wants to snuggle with you all day. Grace has allergies and takes a Benadryl each day. She gets nervous in new situations. They are like 2 peas in a pod, when I separate them for any reason they are constantly looking for each other. I made a bed on my desk and they love being there next to me while I work.

If you're interested in adoption please follow these steps.
Go to our website at Ebarr.org 
Find the tab that says adopt a dog
Locate the Blue Link that says adoption application
Print the application, fill out the application, scan and email back to us at adoptions@ebarr.org
Once approved we can set up a meet and greet. 

Due to the few people who run the rescue and assessment purposes please kindly follow the directions. After you take the above steps you are more than welcome to message or email us questions.

animal.breeds_label: Doberman Pinscher & German Shepherd Dog Mix
animal.description:
Finn was turned into the city kill shelter as an owner surrender because his family had no time for him. The shelter sent out a plea for help for him to get out because he was very scared in the shelter and was not showing well for potential adopters. He was added to the daily euthanasia list. He didn't deserve to die because he was scared. We went and picked him up from the shelter and took him into rescue. He has done much better in his foster home. He is housetrained and crate trained and we have been working with him on leash training. He is absolutely gorgeous.  We did a DNA test on Finn.  His results are as follows:  41.6% Doberman Pinscher, 22.9% German Shepherd Dog, 15.6% Siberian Husky, 5.4% Chow Chow, and 14.5% blend of Berger Picard, Dutch Shepherd and Belgian Malinois.  He weighs 48 pounds and is about 1.5 years old. He loves to run and loves to play with other dogs. He is friendly with people. No cats for Finn, he likes to chase them. An apartment setting is not going to be an appropriate situation for Finn's energy level and size.

Finn's adoption fee is $350. Finn has been fully vaccinated, neutered and microchipped so he is ready to go! Finn is currently located in his foster home in Sheridan, TX and will remain there until adopted.

1020015

I need a single family home with a fenced in yard since I require lots of physical and mental stimulation!

I am also heartworm positive. Heartworm is NOT contagious. The rescue covers the cost of treatment at the rescue's vet. 

Do you love getting puppy kisses? Giving belly rubs? Seeing happy tippy tap dances? Then Sierra might just be the dog for you! Sierra is a goofball and is as sweet and happy as they come. She loves her people and I would swear she tries to make you laugh (her go-to is wiggling around on her back and trying to spin in a circle from that position). Shes doing great on a leash, and is perfectly house trained. She gets along well with our little dogs (aside from the occasional paw to the face); no exposure to cats or children so not sure on that. Sierra will take time to warm up to younew things make her nervous, but were working on it! If you have the patience to help her gain confidence and get used to her new surroundings, youll be rewarded with one of the most loving dogs you could ever ask for!

animal.description:
Barks and Meows Rescue introduces Bear. He is almost 3 years old and is a Husky/Shepherd mix. He weighs 65lbs. He has a medium hair coat. Bear was surrendered to our Rescue after his family fell on difficult times and he and the other unneutered males in the home were not getting along. Multiple dogs in an apartment didn't work for this guy. He has done very well in his foster home where he has a resident female alpha dog to play with every day. He really has enjoyed being with the 4 kids in the home ages 12-16. He is crate trained but only goes in it if he wants to as he is housebroken, Bear was raised with cats and would sometimes chase them. He still pulls a bit on his walk if he sees a squirrel, and is a very strong solid boy. He has come out of his shell since bringing Mili the other foster dog into the home. He was too bossy with the first female dog that was fostered with him so we brought in Mili who quickly showed him who the Queen was going to be. He is allowed on the furniture and basically sleeps where he wants, on the furniture, on the dog bed, in his crate, or sometimes on the floor in his foster parent's room. Bear is a wonderful family dog. He would be fine with or without another canine in the home. If there is another dog, it will need to be a female and one who is the alpha. He loves to give kisses and cuddles. He will bark if someone comes to the door, typical of his breed mix. He rides well in the vehicle. He has been great with children ages 6 and over as per his previous owners. He is a wonderful family dog. Currently, Bear is crated, when his foster family is all out of the house. The ideal home for our Bear is one where someone in the home is home. He is used to having someone around him all the time. Another well socialized, a female alpha dog would work as well. Since he is on the timid side, we would recommend more of a quiet home and one not based in the heart of the city. Since he is known to chase cats, a cat-free home is best. Bear is now neutered, up to date with vaccines, 4DX tested negative, and is on heartworm prevention/flea/tick prevention until December. A fully fenced yard and a Veterinarian History of Compliance are mandatory to apply for Bear.
Visit barksandmeows.ca for an online application. Available to Ontario Residents only!!!

animal.description:
Oliver is a 3 year old Collie mix. He was owner surrendered in October 2020 and arrived at the rescue. 

Here is Oliver's story - He was tied to tree outside for his life. He had interaction with some other dogs on the property where he lived but he wasn't socialized with people. 

When he first arrived at the rescue he would growl and snap at us - all because he was so scared. But, with repeatedly trying to coax him over and slowly petting him, he has come out of his shell with all of the volunteers. 

Now, with new people we assume he will act the same way he did when he arrived at the rescue, so Oliver will be adoptable only to people in Arkansas/Missouri and they would need to come to the rescue several times to meet Oliver and let him get to you you. 

One suggestion would be a family with no children, a quiet surrounding, and possibly a farm or big yard for him to run around in. 

He has recently started playing with toys - we don't think he ever had any before. 

Email us at gailspets@hotmail.com for more information on Oliver, or call Gail directly.

animal.description:
Registered Name: AJN Just a Dream
Call Name: Dream
Birth Date:  July 25, 2017
Color: Black
Pedigree: Defrim Bale--PJ Just a Dream)
PRISON TRAINED GREYHOUND

As his name implies, Dream is truly a Dream Dog!  He is smart, gentle, affectionate, loves everyone, and constantly wags his tail.  As you can see from his photos, he has a beautiful, shiny coat. He gets along well with the other greyhounds in his foster home, and is enjoying his new world as a pet.  He is not demanding, walks easily by your side while on leash, stands quietly for a bath and to trim his nails, is quiet and easy going in the house, and is just a really nice fellow.  Dream is also a smaller greyhound at just 67lbs.  He will come to you fully vetted (neutered, teeth cleaned, vaccines updated, and macro chipped.) He is not good with cats.

Despite his small size, Dream was a really good racer. He competed in 59 races and won 8 times. He also had 132nd places.  He was even a Grade A racer, and stakes contender, which means he was among the fastest dogs on the track.  He is a son of the famous Australian greyhound, Defrim Bale, and his lineage includes Djays Octane, Flying Penske, and Oswald Cobblepot.  Dream is a really nice dog with a great pedigree as well as a great personality! He will make a super companion for the family lucky enough to adopt him.

Dream has just graduated from  the Greyhound Advancement Center's greyhound training program.  He knows the following commands:  sit, lie down, go to place (his bed or mat), wait at the door, heel, stay, come on recall, and leave it.  He will be ready with his new owner to test for the Canine Good Citizen award, or to become a certified therapy dog.  The inmate trainers really enjoy having the greyhounds at Hardee, and the dogs love all the treats and attention they get.  The inmate trainers are able to earn state sponsored certifications, which they can use to gain employment when they are released.  It is a really nice way for the dogs to become socialized and learn their basic commands, as well as giving the inmates something positive to do while they are incarcerated.  

Dream's $600 adoption fee includes his neuter, teeth cleaning, vaccines, Bordetella (to protect against kennel cough), microchip, leash and collar, adoption guide, BAGA identification tag, and prison training. Your adoption fee helps us to defray some of the veterinary and care costs we have incurred for Dream, and will help us to continue our work on behalf of the greyhounds.   For more information or to meet Dream, please contact us at BAGA@tampabay.rr.com. For more information on greyhounds as pets, or to submit an application to adopt  this greyhound, please go to our website: www.bayareagreyhounds.org.   Dream is being fostered in the Tampa Bay area.

Millie, a very sweet fawn horse coat, was taken to a shelter and from
there to Operation Scarlet. Information from the paperwork given to
Operation Scarlet seemed to indicate this wasn’t the first time this
girl lost her home. Given her happy-go-lucky personality with a tail
that never stops wagging, it’s hard to believe Millie was so unlucky.
Millie loves attention from the volunteers and will run from one to the
other, tail wagging, with a toy or chew bone in her mouth. Millie will
be happy to be the only pet in the house; actually she prefers it that
way. If you’re interested in meeting Millie, please go to the Operation
Scarlet web site, operationscarlet.com, and fill out an application.
Hours are by appointment only.

animal.description:
Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Murphy

Dog's Approximate Age: 1 year

Gender: Male

Dog's Size: Medium (50lbs to 70lbs. as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 52 pounds

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Don't know yet

Good with kids?: Yes, all ages

Any medical issues?: None

Crate trained?: Working on it

House trained?: Working on it

Heartworms?: No

12/9/20: Hello! Murphy here. So I have made a lot of progress with potty training since the last update! I can ring a bell to go out when I need to. I love water so my foster parents take it up before bedtime so I don't need to go in the middle of the night. I am settling in nicely, and am doing great on walks around the neighborhood. I am still wary of most people, but warm up quickly. I recently went to the vet for 'boy surgery' and I do NOT like my collar, but I am healing nicely. I still love to cuddle in the bed at night, which is hard right now with this cone on! But everything should be back to normal soon. I am learning to play with my toys outside when my foster sisters aren't up for playing. I love running around in the backyard with toys in my mouth! I am also finding my voice, and like to bark only when playing. When folks come to the door, I don't make noise, I just sit on the couch and let my foster sisters investigate! I can't wait to meet my furever family!

11/17/20: My name is Murphy and I am 1 year old! I have a great personality and a wild spirit! I have so much fun with my foster sisters. They are opening up to me as I am with them after only a week! I have learned several tricks while being fostered and am always ready to learn more! I am poised to play at a moments notice and love to cuddle too! I am learning to stay in the yard as well as fetch, but you better be willing to play! I love meal time, and I am learning that I shouldn't get too close to my sisters when they are eating, but I am not food aggressive. I am still potty training, but am learning to ring a bell when I need to go out! My foster family lets me sleep in the bed so I am definitely loving that. I like being near my humans, and love to play! I would make a great little brother to a family with a younger dog, or children. I still act like I am a puppy and have an endless amount of energy!

_____________________________________________________________________________

Come visit carolinaboxerrescue.org to learn more about me and see more pictures. Learn about our adoption process too!

_____________________________________________________________________________

animal.description:
Ever wanted a German Shepherd but thought they're too big for you? You need to meet Annalyse.

Annalyse is a little over 1 -year-old, female shepherd mix who weighs around 40-pounds - significantly smaller than most shepherds. She is also already house, leash, and crate/pen-trained and will go to her room/pen when you ask.

Unlike a lot of dogs, Annalyse is pretty self-sufficient and not at all needy. She doesn't require a lot of attention. She enjoys running, playing, and doing zoomies (high energy running around a fenced yard).

Annalyse is excellent when walking on-leash, but she is a little skittish - so her foster recommends double-leashing. Annalyse loves other dogs and will greatly benefit from having a companion dog and a fenced yard where she can be outdoors doing her zoomies. We aren't yet sure about cats.

With her intelligence, Annalyse is very attuned to learning - a few treats and positive reinforcement go a long way. Annalyse is best in a quiet home with an adopter who will give her space to adjust on her terms. She is truly a beautiful dog, and she will make someone a great companion.

Complete an adoption application and come to meet her. Her foster mom will be happy to tell you all about Annalyse.

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

animal.description:
Adoptable in: MA, RI, NH, CT, and VT

Good with dogs: Yes, with proper intros
Good with cats: Unknown
Good with kids: No
Crate trained: Working on it
House trained: Mostly

Brownie is a special dog who needs a special, child free home. He had a very tough upbringing and still has trust issues because of his early years. Since being in rescue, Brownie has made considerable strides. Brownie is very much a person-dog and wants to be with his person as much as possible. He will shadow his person around the house: supervise cooking, chores, and naps. Brownie takes a while to warm up for petting but does seek close contact (lap sitting) almost immediately. He is trying very hard to be a good boy and when he slips up and reacts to a scary situation with aggression, he quickly realizes his overreaction and tries to make amends.
Brownie travels in a crate quite nicely even though cars are concerning and he cries at first. He recently got rave reviews at his vet. Brownie plays fetch with squeaky toys, loves going on walks, exploring fenced in yard, and mostly laying on or near his person. If necessary, he will use a pee pad indoors but if kept on a schedule, it shouldn't be needed. Brownie sleeps a solid 9 hours uncrated at night without incident.
Brownie has been through more than any little guy should have to go through and is looking for a quiet home to spend his senior years.

Please Note: All dogs are posted until they are officially adopted. This dog may have other interested adopters in line. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application on our website at www.lasthopek9.org.

Questions? Please email adoptions@lasthopek9.org. For more photos, or information on upcoming adoption events where you can meet her, please go to www.lasthopek9.org or go to our Facebook page. Thank you for your interest in saving a life!

animal.description:
Shiloh was rescued on 8/23/20 with all the dog bites all over her body, teeth filled down, infection, swollen limps, broken ribs, tail, etc...She was a bait dog!

Was on pain med and antibiotics for a long while. She has has problem walking with pain on her right rear knee.
Surgery to correct knee problem on 11/3/2020.

Now, Shiloh goes for physical therapy (PT) at the vet in Santa Clarita, Los Angeles, once per week for 5 weeks. She goes to water therapy in Bakersfield, Kern County, CA,  once per week as long as she needs it  in addition to PT. A hectic schedule for both her and her committed foster!


Shiloh is a trooper tolerating the tough therapies. Everyone loves her wherever she goes (vet office, Fur and Feathers water therapy place, etc...).

She has been on antibiotics for her nasal infection and will get spayed after the infection is gone.
She cannot receive any vaccination till her nasal infection is cleared by the vet.

Took one horrible person to put her through a dog ring as a bait dog. It takes a whole village to help Shiloh on the road of recovering, experiencing love, compassion, safe, no hungry, no frighten.

We are taking pre-adoption application. Till she is clear of her infection, spayed, she stays with her foster for both physical therapy, water therapy.

Julia does great in the car. Julia is dog selective, She has lived with a dog in the past but it has been quite some time. We are currently recommending she be an only dog. No cats or small animals. Julia has prey drive as is common in most terrier breeds. We have never met a toy that Julia couldn’t destroy so we do not give her toys for fear she will eat them. Julia is loving. When she is happy there is not a piece of her that doesn’t wiggle. She eats dry food and loves bulky sticks. Julia wants a loving adult companion to shower her with affection. In return you will get her undying loyalty and love.

Please contact Lyn (lyn@pawsandprayers.org) for more information about this pet.
No Cats, No Kids

Hunter has a pretty unique look and a sweet personality to match. He is very loving and playful. He gets along well with my dogs but may not do well with smaller dogs because he has a pretty healthy prey drive. He has been known to dispose of opossum, raccoons and squirrels.

Hunter can get nippy/snappy if he is in a house with a lot of drama. I am fairly certain he has some healer or cattle dog in him somewhere. He is very loyal and loves his human. He needs an owner that leads in a firm and fair fashion.

While he appears to be a wire hair terrier of some sort his hair is very soft, almost powdery. He tends to stay clean even with puddles around and loves his toys. Balls, tug toys, bones, are all favorites. He should have a crate because it helps keep him grounded and he is an easy keeper, taking treats nice and loves to sleep on the couch, dog bed, in his crate or at the foot of my bed. He does not appear to chew up furniture but I would not recommend giving him stuffed toys so that stays the case.

Adoption fee is $250. All Paws and Prayers animals are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, up to date on flea/tick/heartworm prevention and microchipped. Non-obligatory adoption applications (available here - https://pawsandprayers.org/adopt/adoption-process-and-application/ ) are required to be submitted prior to scheduling a meeting and greet.

animal.description: Say hi to Nikki! This gorgeous gal came to us from Louisiana after being displaced during the recent hurricane. She is 6 years young and weighs 48 pounds. Nikki loves to play fetch, run zoomies, look out the window, and snuggle with her human friends. While she loves all people, Nikki is not a fan of other dogs and would do best in a home without other animals.  Currently in foster care, she is good with her human foster sisters, ages 6 and 8, likes running along the fence with her foster's neighbor dogs and learning how to sit/ lay down.  She’s certainly a fast learner as she’s sitting on command now.  Nikki has not had any issues being left home alone but LOVES a good car ride when she’s invited to tag along.  Completely house and potty trained, Nikki has done great in a home environment (crates are not her cup of tea) and is content to lie on the couch and watch a good movie or snuggle.  She also walks well using a harness with no leash pulling, loves to roll on her back, and has become the biggest lap dog (just ask her foster dad)!  While she loves her food, she is a gentle eater and acts like such a lady at meal times!  Nikki would be a great addition to a family or someone looking for a loyal companion and doesn't mind a sweet little lady hanging out with them all the time!  If you're looking for a sweet, goofy and cuddly canine buddy, who loves to play with tennis balls, Nikki is it!

animal.description:
Katana (6 year old female, 105 pounds) and Kosmo (2 year old male, 102 pounds)are a bonded pair of Great Pyrenees. They were surrendered by their owner when she fell on hard times and could no longer afford to feed both of them and herself. They were beloved pets who are now confused by this turn of events. Kosmo is a super laid back guy who isn't phased by much of anything. Katana is a little jealous of other dogs around Kosmo, especially other ladies, so she would prefer a home with no other dogs. Both think cats are tasty snacks, so they need a no cat home. Both of them love people and are very gentle, so kids 12+ should be just fine. They walk nicely on leash, but require a fenced yard to call their own. They keep their kennel run clean, so are most likely housebroken. Katana and Kosmo are looking for a new home where they can spend the rest of their lives together, being loved for the majestic fuzz buckets they are. Great Pyrenees, or other livestock guardian experience is a plus.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description: French Fry's foster family reports - French Fry has lots of super cute/positive traits. He's a mellow boy who loves to just hang out. His favorite past-time is cuddling, and he does not understand personal space. When he snuggles, no matter how close he is to you, he wants to be closer! He's extremely gentle when taking food from your hand, and has zero food aggression towards people. He's our only foster we've ever had that doesn't care for peanut butter, which i think is hilarious! He loves a good game of fetch... he will show a tennis ball who's boss! We're working on drop it right now, when he brings it back. :-) He's definitely trainable! He's very graceful and light on his feet. We call it twinkle toes! He bonds quickly to humans, and if he knows you're his person, he is the most loyal dog ever and will make someone such a good companion, but would likely do best as the only pet in the home. Want to learn more? Email French Fry's foster family at varvaro@pacificu.edu.

animal.description:
Please only send inquires to the email in this bio all others will not be answered. Please read the bio before sending questions - we answer all we know about the dog here.

Si came to Heidi's Legacy from a rural shelter in Georgia. He is believed to be between 1-2 yrs old, loves to pay, cuddle and needs a family to love this holiday season. He is great with other dogs. Si is scheduled to be neutered/microchipped and completely vaccinated. He is currently on flea and heartworm preventative.

Si's adoption fee is $300 - He will need to complete obedience training once adopted.

Obedience training is also required for all our pups. We understand with what is going on in the world that this may be a bit delayed. Please email us the completion certificate.

To apply to foster or adopt please fill out application at

www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

Thank you for completing the application. We are all volunteers and short on time, we will contact you back only if we have more questions or your application is approved and you will be invited to meet the dog. We apologize for not being able to answer everyone back.

For more information contact Kelly.V@HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

DOGS are in Foster Homes. There is NO shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

**See our website for more information. www.HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

All communication is thru email so please be patient with us. We are all volunteers and work full time jobs and have families of our own.

It takes anywhere between 3-7 days to process an application - the more complete the application the easier it is for us to process it. Please notify your vet that we will be contacting them and to release information to us.

ADOPTION PROCESS:

1. Complete this application
www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

***Everyone must submit an application - we only keep them on file for 1 month

2. Application background check, vet check, etc

animal.description:
Louise, 11 months old, 40 lbs. Good with dogs and kids over 12. Must have another dog in the home of similar size and must have a securely fenced yard.

Meet Louise! This wonderful girl was part of a litter of puppies born on a rural property. The pups were not socialized or handled by humans until 8 months of age. As a result, Louise is shy with humans. She is making great progress and clearly wants to be with her person and follows her foster mom around the house. With time, she will get there but she will likely never be a social butterfly but a one-on-one love.

Louise is getting more confident every day and is adorable when she plays. She loves running around the yard at high speed. She loves cuddles and belly rubs.

Louise is just a lovely pup who needs a person to help her continue to gain confidence. She walks on a leash and is getting the hang of it but still needs a home with a yard and a secure fence. She does not have a mean bone in her body, but living with young kids is probably a bit stressful for her since she is not very confident. She cannot live with cats.

Louise is bonded to her sister Lola, who is also with us, and in order to thrive in a new home, she will need another dog pal to live with her. We would like to see her in a more residential neighborhood rather than a busy part of town simply due to noise.

She is now updated on all shots, spayed, and is chipped. Her adoption fee is $495 and you can submit an application via savinggreatanimals.org

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
“Listen up, Fives; a Ten is speaking” - Jenna Maroney, 30 Rock 
 
Introducing Jenna! At 11 months old and around 40 pounds, Jenna is the tallest of her sisters, Pearl and Aurora. We expect them to get just a little bit bigger before they are all done growing! 
 
Jenna is still in her puppy stage, and she is learning so much about the world every day. She is fully crate trained, and she is almost housebroken. This little pup is able to sleep soundly all night long in her crate without having to be let outside to go to the bathroom, and when she is let outside, she takes care of business quickly. When Jenna is in a new space, the crate is where she feels most comfortable because the rest of the world can be really scary, and she likes to observe how things look before she’s ready to jump in. With time and patience, Jenna will break out of her shell and see how great the world can be. 
 
New places and people can be a little scary, but Jenna is confident around other dogs and is ready to play! She loves to run around the backyard, play chase, and sprint up and down stairs to get a furry friend to play with her. Jenna will dramatically flop down on a dog bed or roll around on the couch in the hopes that someone will see she’s in a playful mood and come to investigate and join in on the fun. With a bit more confidence with her two-legged friends, Jenna will likely become a dog that likes a good trip to the dog park to meet more four-legged furry friends. 
 
Jenna is very slow to warm up to humans, but she is gaining confidence every day. When she first arrived at her foster home, she would flinch and tuck her tail under her legs when someone would slowly reach for her to give her affection, but she is doing that less and less and is now giving nose kisses and tail wags when she’s happy to see a familiar friendly face. Jenna loves some cuddle time on the couch for head scratches and snuggles once she trusts enough to be able to close her eyes and relax.
 
Unlike a lot of young dogs, Jenna has been a star student on the leash! Going for a walk or short jog is one of Jenna’s favorite activities, and she loves to burn off some of that puppy energy while getting to take a look at what’s going on outside of her house -- from a safe distance, of course. 
Even though Jenna’s personality sounds more like she should be labeled a weenie dog rather than a shepherd-hound mix, Jenna’s got so much potential to blossom into a happy, healthy, and confident gal ready to tackle life with a new family. Contact us today if you think Jenna might be the right fit for you! 

If you’d like to be considered to adopt, the first step in the process is to submit an application through our website: http://athenscaninerescue.com/adoption-procedures/. Our adoption fee is $250 per dog over the age of 6 months and $300 per dog 6 months or younger. We accept payment by Venmo, PayPal, or card.

This includes: basic vet care (i.e. basic vaccinations, including boosters completed after adoption, spay/neuter, heartworm/flea preventatives, and treatment for any health needs while in our care), a microchip, a week’s worth of food for the trial-period, and a harness lead.

We typically adopt to homes within 30 minutes of Athens, GA, as we require a basic home check to ensure all dogs are placed in a safe environment. If you are further away than that and are interested in one of our pups, please still fill out an application and we can discuss your options. 

We do not have a facility and operate through a network of foster homes. Thus, we do not have a phone number. If you’d like to discuss potential adoptions, please email at adopt@athenscaninerescue.com.

animal.description:
Introducing Castle. This handsome guy is around a year old. He is a young, energetic, active and athletic dog. Castle has a lot of great characteristics but he also has some quirks about him that will require an experienced owner. Castle has had a tough first year of his life and has been bounced around to multiple homes before ending up at the city shelter. He was lucky and found a foster with Friends of Rescue and we have been working hard on training and working on his anxiety behaviors. Castle does have some generalized anxiety as well as separation anxiety. With a structured home and a family that instills boundaries and training. Castle does know how to jump a 9 foot privacy fence with ease so his next home will have to prepare to learn how to care for his escape artist self. Castle's ideal home would be with an active family that will take him on hikes, runs, walks, bike rides and trips to the dog park. Castle currently lives with 4 other dogs before young and old, active and lazy. Castle loves to play with other dogs and would love to have another dog in his next home. He is good with cats but sometimes he chases them to try to play. We do not know how he is with children, he does jump so I would suggest no small children. If you are interested in adopting Castle please fill out an application on our website www.forrescue.net.

Castle’s next home needs to be his forever home, so please only serious inquires! He is being fostered in Harvest,AL. If you are interested in adopting please fill out an application on our website www.forrescue.net.

This perfect little love nugget is Mogwai. She's squatty, snorty, extremely sweet and the happiest little girl around. She has a shining personality that evokes happiness and joy immediately upon entering a room. You truly can't be sad when she's around. 



There's so much to love about this sweet little girl. She just loves life no matter what it throws at her. And just look at that smile, she is beautiful! She's so outgoing and loves all people, and you better believe ALL the people love her back. She loves to play.... slightly obsessed with tennis balls but any toy will do. She really enjoys a good game of fetch with her friends.



Here in her foster home she has had exceptional behavior! She knows what's a toy and what isn't and she's potty/kennel trained. She absolutely loves TV time at night....she excitedly claims her spot on your lap and snuggles you so hard you've never felt so loved. It's absolutely adorable how she wiggles and squirms into just the right position. I've spent many a nights watching one more episode just so I can have a little bit more of her love. I promise you will too.



This is her second time with KCPP. She was once abandoned and now returned by her adoptive family of 2 years due to no fault of her own. 

She's just asking for a chance at a home that will love her for the rest of her days. In return, she will promise many laughs and future snuggles, and make a great walking partner. I promise she'd make the absolute most of the life you can offer her. She needs to be an only pet, can live with older children and will most certainly be your best friend! Give this sweet girl a chance and make her dreams come true!



If you want to turn your gray skies blue and your frown upside down, then email her foster mom at ang35847@aol.com.... she is sure to be the sunshine of your life and without a doubt you will be hers!

animal.description: YOU MUST BE 21 YEARS OF AGE OR OLDER TO ADOPT ABOUT ME: My name is Lulu and I am ready for my forever home. I am up to date on my vaccines and I have been spayed. I also have a micro chip. I was adopted in 2008 and moved to Texas with my new family. They moved back to Mobile into a home that doesn't allow dogs. I am now looking for another home. I am a senior dog, but don't let that scare you away. I am in great shape for my age and you don't have to worry about house training me or getting up in the middle of the night to take me on a potty break. I enjoy napping! I am easy going and loveable. I can be protective of my owner, but very obedient. Please go to www.mobilespca.org and complete an online adoption application and someone from the office will give you a call and set up an appointment for you to come meet me. ADOPTION FEE: $100 Heart Worm Negative 50 Pounds 13 Years Old ABOUT OUR PETS: All of our pets available for adoption have been spayed/neutered, tested for heartworms, given age-appropriate vaccinations, microchipped and are on flea and heartworm preventative medication. ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS: To give each dog the best possible home we require a completed Adoption Application. Screening and approval by our Adoption Coordinators and a home visit may be required to make sure this pet fits into your home and the home fits our pet. CONTACT US:If you would like to give this dog a good home please call the Mobile SPCA office at 251-633-3531 or drop by our Adoption Center located at 620 Zeigler Circle W, Mobile, AL 36608 - Tuesday through Friday from 9 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. and Thursday and Saturday from 9 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. CAN'T ADOPT? SPONSOR OR DONATE! This wonderful animal is just one of many in our care right now. Your sponsorship helps us provide shelter, food, and tender loving care for the animals until they find new loving homes. Adoption fees do not cover our expenses, so your sponsorship will make a positive impact on our organization and especially on our animals’ well being. Please note: we are not a chapter or affiliate of any national animal organization. We are, moreover, very grateful for your generosity. Thank you!

animal.description: Temperance is a female German, 7 to 8 years old, and about 60 lbs. She was an owner surrender in Oklahoma after her master died and was taken to a high kill shelter to be euthanized. She is Heartworm positive and is currently undergoing treatment. Her skin was in horrible shape and she barely had any fur when she was pulled from the shelter. She still gets baths twice a week and is on medication to address her skin issues. This will be an ongoing schedule for awhile. She is very gentle and just wants love. She craves human interaction. She needs a loving home with no small dogs, cats, or small children as she gets excited and can knock them over. Here heartworm treatment will be covered by Hope until she tests negative in a few months. She needs a retirement home where she can just chill, love her family, and be loved and cared for the way she deserves. If you would like to meet Temperance, please complete an online application that can be found at: http://hopeanimalrescueofiowa.org/forms/196/dog-application Adoption fee is $250 which includes spay/neuter, age-appropriate vaccines/tests, and microchip.

animal.description:
BO, shelter number D20-11018, is a young Brittany Spaniel mix male. He is about one year old and weighs about 30 to 35 pounds. He was surrendered by his owner to the shelter for unknown reasons.
BO is a little shy when he meets new people at first, but he warms up quickly when you show him some love and care. He walks well on leash and does love attention. He should fit into just about any household and make a good pet with just alittle adjustment time. He should be good with kids of any age. He should be good with other dogs as he enjoyed visiting with the other shelter dogs through the chain link fence in the runs.
BO is a pretty rugged dog but has short hair and won’t tolerate cold weather very well. We hope his new family can find a place for him to sleep indoors, especially in the winter. He would love to be included in family activities anytime, indoors or out.
BO is looking for a fresh start in a new home. If you think he would be a good fit for your family and would like to meet him for a possible adoption, please come out to the shelter at 109 Commerce Drive in Levelland from 9 AM till noon or from 2:00 to 5:00 PM on any day of the week except Tuesday and Wednesday to meet him. On Tuesday or Wednesday, you will need to make an appointment at least two hours in advance. You can call the shelter during shelter hours (9 till noon and 2 to 5) at (806) 891-0829. To call at other hours, dial (806) 894-6164 and ask to speak with an Animal Control employee. When speaking with an Animal Control employee, be sure to refer to BO by his shelter number, D20-11018. If you would like more information, please send a message through messenger on "The Levelland Animal Shelter” Facebook page.
All our dogs are vaccinated for Parvo, distemper, Bordetella (kennel cough) and most other common dog diseases. We do not vaccinate them for Rabies. There is no adoption fee, but the adopter will be responsible for having the dog spayed or neutered and for the Rabies shot.
Check the Google map for directions to the shelter.

Due to Covid-19 concerns, we are not planning any public adoption events. If you are pre approved , we will call to set up an appointment to come and meet the dog and potentially take them home. It is by appointment only- 
Dogs will be brought into the outdoor kennel for you to meet and make your decision. MASKS WILL BE MANDATORY to maintain EVERYONE'S safety  NO EXCEPTIONS PLEASE !! Unless otherwise noted, the puppies and dogs listed will arrive on Saturday, December 5th, 2020 .
Please follow this link to fill out an application. It is step one in adopting a pup from our rescue.
http://littlerhodyrescue.com/adoption-application/ 

*Filling an application does not guarantee you as the adopter. All applicant's references will be called. PLEASE call your veterinarian and personal references and allow consent to speaking with us ! 
We cannot process your application otherwise. Failure will put your application in 'Limbo"  
We process applications as they arrive. The first approved applicant will be called and the pup taken off of Petfinder. We do not have the man/ woman power to all all other applicants to advise them. 
IF there s another dog that you are interested in as well, please list at the top of the application and we will enter your application for that pup if the first choice has been adopted. 

THANK YOU !!! You are giving a first rate dog a second chance....By adopting! 

***** SADLY , we need to put this in print: THIS IS A RESCUE DOG. We do NOT know their birthday / age.  (unless other wise noted)  
More often than not, OUR TEAM  has saved them from euthanasia in Southern shelters. 
We do not know any more than our Veterinarians offer to us. 
 We often have them in kennels, and utilize crate training.  House training status is often NOT KNOWN. 
Prior Health, estimated weight  (as an adult), breed (Including the parents' breed , size or mix)   and some health concerns are  NOT KNOWN unless our veterinarians discover it and offer the information to us.   Again, these are strays and turn ins from all over the country. They do NOT come with labels; nor guarantees. 

Characteristics and disposition can and will evolve with time.
YOU the adopter are responsible to train and keep up to date on vaccines and preventatives.  
YOU the adopter are responsible for taking care of this new member of your family. 
 *************

****
Our adoption fees are $ 600. This fee includes the transportation of the pet from one of the organizations that we work with in TX, LA or TN. Before joining us in RI all dogs are: spayed/neutered, microchipped, up to date on age-appropriate vaccines, and on de-wormers, flea/tick and heartworm prevention. In addition, all adults (6 months +) are heartworm tested and MUST be negative for both heartworm and microfilaria before transport. 

In addition to the above, all dogs must have a Certificate of Veterinary Inspection and be deemed healthy per USDA law in order to travel. Once they have been certified they are then transported via USDA transport services only, which is required by law. 
 We  sometimes don't understand how bad the situation is for these pups and dogs in southern states.  Many people in the south don't spay or neuter their pets as we do here. Subsequently, there are thousands of beautiful , worthy pups and dogs, kittens and cats  that are dumped, shot, abandoned, brought into shelters, neglected, abused and abandoned.  We step in , tend to their veterinary needs. As you can see above, we never fail to properly spay and neuter. Everything is done with the  caring , capable hands of our veterinarians to get them healthy and ready to place them for adoption. That's when we put the demand for family- friendly pets with the supply ..... 

Give a first rate dog a second chance!!!! ADOPT! 


Keep in mind that we also offer a two week return policy for the return of a healthy dog that includes a full refund. We want to make sure that the adoption is a perfect fit for both you and the dog.

If you would like more information about adopting please select "More About Little Rhody Rescue" where you will also find our online application if you'd like to proceed with the adoption process. Thank you!

animal.description:
Floofy and Houdini are looking for a home together. 
We are requiring a fenced yard for this pair. 
Because of Houdini's shyness, we are looking for an adult home for this pair.
Houdini didn't have much confidence until he met Floofy.  Houdini has been much happier and is soaking up the companionship of his fluffy Floofy.  And Floofy was separated from a dog she had bonded with. Houdini and Floofy live in the same foster home and have really hit it off with each other and hope they can be adopted together. 

Our normal adoption fee is $300 for a dog.  They would have a reduced adoption fee of $500.00 for both dogs.

Floofy, Bichon Mix, 4 yrs , 10lbs, rescued from a home that didn't take good care of her, great with dogs, full of energy, ideal home would include a four-legged playmate named Houdini, fenced yard so I can run and play, when worn out from playing, favorite place to sleep is on your lap

Houdini - Chihuahua Mix, 2yrs, 11lbs,
 Houdini,  when you're not looking, I might run off with your socks or a dryer sheet, a timid little guy but once he gets to know you, your constant companion. loves giving kisses, and being right beside you whether you are sitting on the sofa or cooking in the kitchen, loves snuggling under a blanket and chasing bugs in the yard or squirrels on the fence,  love treats, loud noises and lots of activity can sometimes be scary,  housebroken and working on leash training, best with  fenced yard, adopted with Floory, a diamond in the "ruff", but if you can be patient, he will work his magic on your heart


Requirements for Adoption:
Must live in the Central Ohio area.  For rescues/shelters across Ohio, visit:  ColumbusDogConnection.com/RescuesShelters.html
Must be over the age of 24 to adopt.
Your resident pets must be spayed/neutered.

Adoption Process:
 We do not have an application. Adoptions are pet-adopter driven.
To meet our pets:
Call our office at 614-471-9000 or click on the pet which you are interested in and send email. We will be happy to discuss the adoption process with you and set-up a visit at time of contact. The foster dogs are in foster homes and most of the cats reside at our office.

The adoption process includes a lease manager reference (if applicable) , a veterinarian reference, a home-visit (in-person or virtual).
If you've never owned a pet, part of our adoption process requires that you call several vet offices to compare services, prices, and availability. 
Questions to ask include:
How many doctors are at your practice?
Can I request to see a specific Vet or would I be scheduled with first available?
What are your hours?
How much is:   annual exam, heartworm test & tablets, an x-ray,  vaccines, a non-emergency office call? 
Do you recommend vaccines every year or every three years?  (every 3 yrs as suggested by the AVMA)           

The pooches that visit your home will not be left there at the end of the visit. We take them back home with us so your family can discuss to ensure he/she is a good fit for your home.

There is an adoption agreement and adoption fees as follows:
 $300 for Adult Dogs (6yrs  & younger)
 $200 for Senior Dogs (7 yrs and older)
 $80 for Cats  

 All pets are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, heartworm tested (dogs), fiv/leukemia tested (cats), & micro-chipped.
Known medical conditions are discussed at time of inquiry.
